animal.description:
Preston is an approximately 3 year old American Pit Bull Terrier.

He is very smart, silly, affectionate, and playful. He loves to do zoomies before he goes on walks and can entertain himself with his toys.

Preston loves to run around and play but he is just as happy to curl up on the couch and watch movies.

Preston has received professional behavioral training. He is extremely loyal to those he trusts but needs slow introductions to meet new people. He has been doing very well with meeting new friends!

He just needs to find the right home with someone that is experienced with his breed as well as anxious dogs and has time & patience to work with him. Prestons perfect home is one where he is the only dog and no children.

His foster mom says He has continued to surprise me with how sweet and loving he can be in the face of everything he has gone through.

Although he is still wary of strangers, he has grown to trust us over the last few months and I know in his forever home, he will grow to trust and love even more.

He is located in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.

If you think Preston is the dog for you, send us an email at furlovehaven@gmail.com or complete an application on our website furlovehaven.org.

** Please understand that we are a volunteer run organization and we do our best to respond in a timely manner. Due to the high volume of applications, emails & phone calls we receive, we may be unable to respond to everyone.

The first step is to submit an application via our website furlovehaven.org.

We will review your application and you may be contacted if this animal might be a good fit.

Please be aware, submitting an application is not a guarantee, but if we think you might be a potential fit, someone will contact you within 72 hours.

Feel free to reach out to furlovehaven@gmail.com if you haven't received a response after 72 hours.**

animal.description:
Katie was pulled from a high intake shelter in rural Georgia and is currently living in a Maine foster home. Katie's foster mom has this to say about her: "Katie loves people and gets along with other dogs. She walks well on the leash, is treat motivated, and generally 'eager to please.' She will entertain herself playing with toys, but prefers to be in close company with her people, and can be vocal if left alone."

Katie also has an allergy to grain and so needs to be fed an appropriate diet. At this time, we don't feel a home with cats would be best for Katie. But, she would be great with folks who work from home or are often home and want a big loving dog companion.

All of our animals are examined by a veterinarian, given age-appropriate vaccinations, dewormed, microchipped, spayed or neutered, heartworm tested and treated if necessary. Vet references are required and prior to adoption a home inspection will be conducted.   

Transport options available. Adoption fee applies. 
If interested go to www.pmarinc.org for an application.

animal.description: You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.ATDRThis is Pepper! He was dumped at a shelter by a family member after his beloved owner had to go to a long-term care facility. On top of that, he'd been kept outside and had little or no care after his person was forced to leave him behind due to health issues. Poor boy, he's been one scared and upset guy ATDR's hearts went out to him Pepper is now in a comfortable foster home where he has soft blankets and his own little bed and an abundance of loving care from a kind foster mom. Sadly, Pepper is having trouble adjusting to his circumstances. Hopefully, in time, he'll become comfortable and be willing to trust and can learn to enjoy a new lap and comfortable chair to share with a person or people he can call his own again. When that time comes, if you have it in your heart to give Pepper a happy ending to his sad story, please submit an adoption application for him. He's deserving of love and gentle companionship like he lost when he sadly lost the only home he'd ever known

animal.description: *Special Needs* - Deacon is a 3 years old - a Cattle dog mix - extremely intelligent and sturdy with a strong sense of adventure and an invincible mindset. He’s neutered, vaccinated and microchipped. Deacon was hit by a car in Jan of 2020 & suffered 2 broken legs. He was taken to the shelter where he was going to be PTS. ERF rescue decided to give him a second chance. He underwent 3 complicated surgeries and is now in physical therapy. He gets many gentle daily walks. He is happy to chill in a crate or at your side. He is young and has learned many commands, this guy will flourish with an experienced owner who can give him structure. He will continue to need physical therapy and pain management throughout the rest of his life. He will probably not be able to be let off leash as he’s very energetic & will need to be kept calm so he doesn’t re-injure his legs . Deacon is dog friendly, if properly introduced but would NOT do well with cats or any other small animals, chickens etc.

animal.description:
Jagger is the cutest! He loves staying warm by the fire on these chilly nights! His siblings all got adopted and now it his turn to find a forever family. Jagger is a 5 month old chihuahua mix under 10 lbs. We are guessing maybe dachshund or rat terrier.

He’s been neutered, fully vaccinated, dewormed, and microchipped! He’s doing really good with the potty training and loves sleeping in his crate bundled up in his blankets. 

Jagger would do great in a active home with another doggie playmate to grow up. He fostered in Suisun and we adopt locally as we need to be close enough for meets and a home check. If you are interested please send us a DETAILED email about yourself and lifestyle and request a application to fill out. We will not respond to one sentence emails! We are only adopting to home owners only with a fully fenced in yard. No renters or apartments. After we receive your application to review we set up a phone interview. When approved we will move forward with meets and a home check. It’s about finding the right match for our dogs and potential families! 

Please be patient as we are backed up with emails to get back to. It can take 2-4 weeks for a response. If anyone wants to join our team and volunteer some time to help please let me know! I’m looking for committed people who will put in the time and not flake.

animal.description:
Meet Stryker! This gorgeous boy has been in my home for almost 4 years. That is a very long time to have a foster dog. Stryker is a dog that needs a very experienced home with no other pets. He has come a long way, but he will always be a work in progress. We have him on a schedule and have to constantly be working with him. Stryker can’t be in a home with any animals or children. He is not good with dogs, cats, birds, chickens, none! He would need a strong handler who can take on a dog like him and give him the attention and training. His prey drive is very high and he isn’t a dog for your average dog owner. He is not a dog park dog or a dog that can be off leash. 

Stryker does love people and will be your best buddy once he gets to know you. He does tend to do better with men but likes women too. He really feeds off your vibe. Stryker listens very well and knows all his basic commands. Very food motivated and loves being outside playing with his toys. I can see Stryker loving life with someone who has property where he can run and enjoy being active. It’s been a long road with him, but i won’t fail him. A dog like him wouldn’t have made it out of the shelter or would have ended up in the wrong hands. He was never socialized and has had a rough past.

Stryker is not perfect, but I know he would thrive when he finds a home that he didn’t have to stress about other animals around. I know he’s a dog that will stay with us for a long time, but maybe one day we will find his right home. I love this boy and would do anything for him. 

If you are interested in Stryker and think you are the one for him please send us a detailed message and request a application. He is fostered in Sacramento. Must be a home owner with a secure fence at least 6 feet. No pets and no children. No apartments. He needs a yard.

animal.description:
Rocky Dee was brought to the NYC Animal Care Centers as an owner surrender in August 2020 because his owners were moving..  Due to overcrowding at the shelter,  he was slated for Euthanasia.  Pound Hounds was able to save his life due to a foster stepping up.

While at the shelter he was reasonably stressed as that is what happens at the shelter.  He was slow to come around, however in his foster home and working with a trainer has now made him a great dog.

Rocky Dee's STATS:

Approx 1 year old
60 lbs
House trained 
Crate-Trained
Rocky is high energy due to being 1 year old. Many calmer dogs cannot keep up with him. Rocky enjoys socializing and playing with other dogs. It is preferred Rocky is paired with a high energy dog around the same age as him.  
Kids over 11, please
UTD on vaccinations, neutered and microchipped.

Here is what his foster mom has to say:

The perfect home for Rocky will consist of active people. Rocky will do best with multiple walks and outlets for his energy daily. Heavy-duty puzzle toys, hikes, jogs, playtime with similar tempered dogs are great ways to get his energy out. 

At this age, he cannot be left alone because he will get into things.  Best if not home to crate him.  He knows the words NO so please use them.  His foster Mom Is constantly training him but it will take time due to Rocky being a pup.  That is why it is best to tire him out during the day.  A tired dog is a happy dog!!


Rocky is a fun dog where he will keep you on your feet.  There is never a dull moment with Rocky Dee. He is always happy.  He loves to lean in on his human so he can get petted, loves to go for walks or play in the yard.

animal.description:
Meet ANDREW. Yes, really. He's really this cute. He comes to us from a Houston area shelter because he is heartworm positive. We provide the heartworm treatment through our clinic, so that expense is covered for adopters. Andrew REALLY likes men. While he is fine with women, he really really enjoys a home where he can get plenty of male bonding time. He is super unique looking, and is really a good boy. He can be a bit grouchy and grumbly around younger kids, so we prefer a home with older kids only.

Is Andrew a Lhasa? A Norfolk? Oh, who the heck knows. All we know is he is crazy cute and in need of a family. Can we get him one? To have your home considered for adoption, read about our adoption process or fees, and find out about interstate transport, please visit our website, www.LongWayHomeAdoptables.org and click the adopt tab!

Our adoption fee is $200 for dogs, $100 for cats, and it includes spay/neuter, all vaccines, heartworm testing, fecal testing, deworming, flea/heartworm prevention, and a microchip. 

NATIONWIDE TRANSPORT available for an additional $200 fee. See our website for more info!

Please note: breed listings are based on educated guesses. Shelter animals and abused pets do not come with DNA profiles, so breeds listed on the profile are based on size, coat, markings, and body shape, but are in no way guaranteed. 

_______

Long Way Home is a volunteer organization, comprised of a network of foster homes. Please keep this in mind, as we only have so much time to volunteer around full time jobs, family obligations, etc. It may take us several days to respond.

animal.description:
Tinker Bell  (I call her Think) is 8 years old and is 21LBS. She was a stray and end it up at the Shelter. When I met her she was depressed on a bed waiting. She was not doing so good, sleeping all day, very sad to see. Like someone had abandoned her.  At first I thought she was overweight but discovered her body is actually shaped that way. She loves her walks, always ready to go!! She is potty trained and is a good eater. One thing she does which is hilarious is going to my closet and get my shoes then bring them to her bed and play with them. She doesn't damage them and even if you think she chews them, she doesn't. She is so funny, what a character!! She will bring anything she finds in her bed, T-shirt, socks. She will put everything in a circle and then sleep with it. She is with 3 other dogs right now but would be better as the queen of the house. She loves in the morning going out in her yard and sniff around. Take her time and go in and out all day long. We have doggie doors and she knows how to take use them. Would be great if someone likes to garden. 
She listen well and would make a great companion. if you are interested in helping this title one please email at pets@findahomegiveahome.com
she is vetted, microchip and spayed. adoption fee is $100.00 . She just had a dental and got Pro heart 12 which is a shot to prevent Heartworm prevention for 12 months. All ready to go!! You will need a little patience with her but at the end of the day she will be a great little companion with character. 
the shelter had her as Dachshund mix.

animal.description:
His name is Sampson for short, he is approximately 4 yo, and he is a beautiful German Shepard. Besides being handsome, Sampson is intelligent, athletic, and a great companion. He is a good hiking partner and loves to run! This guy has a heart of gold....he is ready and eager to be someone's BFF! 

We were able to raise enough funds to send him to an intensive 4 week board and train program. (Not that it was actually needed, we just didn't have any available foster homes and he was starting to succumb to kennel stress in the shelter and we knew we had to get him out of there ASAP). 

He did GREAT during training, and is now thriving with his awesome foster family in Santa Cruz. His adoption will also come with five free in home private training sessions by his trainer to show his new family everything he knows, etc. (Rescue dogs rarely come with almost $2K worth of a training background!)

His forever home and family will definitely be the better ones for it as Sampson is truly a special guy -- could it be you??

animal.description: Sweet Talcum is a 40 lb lap dog! She is around 2 years old and likely a mix of a few different breeds but may have some Lab and Terrier in her. She is always happy and very affectionate with people. Talcum has been fostered with a few other dogs, big and small, and got along with all of them. When she sees other dogs on walks, she tends to get a little over excited mainly because she wants to play! She is also currently fostered with a couple of kitties and while she barks at them through the baby gate, she's polite and respectful of them when they are right in front of her. Talcum is house trained in her current foster home and sleeps quietly on her dog bed through the night. While she loves lap snuggles, she is also quite content to go take a snooze on her own on her dog bed. Talcum loves to play and rip apart her toys. She is working on not being mouthy in playtime and is quickly picking up her basic commands, especially when chicken is involved. She has done well around the kids (6 and 7 years old) that she has been around. She recently had surgery for an old leg injury and is the newest member of the tri-pawed club. She gets along just fine without her leg and will be available for adoption mid-February. If you think you are ready to add to your family by adopting mama Talcum when she is ready, then fill out an adoption application on our website today! We recommend completing the application process and connecting with a adoption coach before looking for a dog or puppy you'd like to adopt. If you're already approved to adopt or if you've adopted from Labs and More before, connect with your adoption coach for the next steps. Your interest in adopting a rescued dog or puppy from Labs and More Rescue is appreciated! Please find our adoption information at www.labsandmore.org. Your adoption donation provides funding for Labs and More, a nonprofit organization which is supported solely by Volunteers and funded by donations. Good news is your adoption donation can be considered tax deductible. So much care is provided to your new dog prior to the adoption, including: spay and neuter, microchip, veterinarian visit(s), vaccinations, and other medical care as needed. Many of the dogs we rescue require extensive surgeries and care prior to adoption. Please understand we are unable to predict future behavior or medical needs of your adopted dog. We provide no guarantees regarding behavior, breed, or age of the dogs. Thank you for rescuing.Thank you for looking to Adopt a Labrador Retriever or other Mixed Breed Dog from California Labradors Retrievers and More Rescue. Please take a moment and go to www.labsandmore.org and click on Adopt to complete our online dog adoption application. If you have any questions email us at doginfo@labsandmore.org or call us at 858-273-5386. Thank you for looking to a rescue group to fulfill your dream of adding a new dog to your life! Dogs + Love = Family

- Great mix of playful and affectionate; loves to be with you as you go about your day

animal.description:
Meet Miss Piper, our tripod princess! Currently in a foster home in the Collierville area, we would love to arrange a meeting!  The first step to adopting Piper would be to complete an application at www.perfectmatchanimalrescue.org.  Piper is 5 years old and weighs approx 68lbs.  Read on for more information!

Piper was hit by a car in June and found herself at Memphis Animal Shelter and was close to being euthanized. Thankfully, and in no small part due to her foster family stepping up, we were able to rescue her.  Between June and October, Piper had 4 different orthopedic surgeries to try to save her leg. When it became apparent that those efforts had failed, Piper went through amputation surgery in November. On top of that, the rescue also treated Piper for heartworms! We are happy to report that Piper is finally heartworm negative, she is healed from her surgeries, spayed, fully vaccinated, and is now ready to find her forever home. Piper is around 5 years old, settled, housebroken and is content to be with her person. She is intensely loyal, loves chin scratches, a soft bed and plenty of treats. She has been in a foster home with 5 other large dogs and a cat. She has tried to chase the cat but stops when told no. She would probably be best in a home with older children and one that has calmer dogs or no other dogs as she would adore being the center of attention and she will make the lucky family that adopts her the center of her world.  Please don't hesitate to reach out for more information.

home_environment_attributes.other_animals: Piper will do best with calm dogs.  She has tried to chase a cat, but stopped when told no.  She co-exists with multiple dogs and a cat in her foster home. Would perhaps enjoy a quieter enviroment.

animal.description:
This dog is part of our shelter outreach program where we take dogs from overcrowded shelters in hopes of finding them a forever home here! We generally do not have much background info on them and cannot guarantee they are housebroken. They are all up to date on vaccines, spayed/neutered and microchipped.
1 yr old. 50lbs. Transferred up from LA where she was surrendered by her owner as a result of the hurricane, poor JoJo sadly spent most of her young life cooped up in a crate. She appears housebroken and keeps her kennel very clean. She is very sweet. High energy so we are looking for an active family, a runner would be great! Breeds are a best guess, Shepherd, Border Collie, and some Pittie in there too we think. A home that is familiar with the breeds and their needs is also recommended. She is very smart and does know some commands. And we heard she would ring a bell to go potty! She is a herding breed so older kids may be better. Obedience training will be necessary, she needs leash manners (a puller). JoJo loves to be near people and cannot wait to be with a family for the holidays. Home with a fenced in yard required. *Per JSAC policy, puppies and kittens under 6 months will not be adopted to families with children under the age of 6 years.

animal.description:
Looking for a new best friend? Look no further! My name is Ossie, and I’m a 10-year-old Chug (Chihuahua/Pug) in search of my forever home! Don’t let my age fool you… I’m an energetic guy with so much love to give!

In my foster home, I love to play with my foster brothers, who are much bigger than me. When I’m not playing with other dogs, I’m a huge snuggle bug, and love to cuddle up with my foster parents and their young kiddos, who are 4 and 5 years old. When it’s time to go to sleep, I prefer to be snuggled up in bed with my foster parents. I would be happiest in a home where I could spend most of the day by my human’s side! I can be a little shy at first, but I warm up to new people in just a few days. I have had a few accidents in the house, but my foster parents say this improved once I got acclimated to my new environment! My new family may need to be a bit patient with me as I adjust to my forever home.

 To summarize, my favorite things in life include playing with my foster brothers, snuggles, and spending quality time with my foster family. Do you think I sound like a good match for your family? I hope so! I look forward to meeting you!  Just ask for me, Ossie, on your application today!

animal.description:
Poor 11 year old Artemis (AKA Artie) has already spent several holidays now without a home.

He loves all the staff and volunteers that give him extra love and attention, but he is patiently waiting for a forever home of his very own.  He has so much love and companionship to give!

Quick stats:
- Housebroken
- Crate experience
- Good house manners
- Loves to get neck/chest scratches, belly rubs, and snuggles
- Excellent kisser
- Medium energy level (calm in the house, but always excited to join you for daily walks!)
- Expert napper
- Knows “Sit”, and is currently working on mastering “Down”, “Crate”, and “Wait.”  Loves treats and training time! 

- Loves car rides and is a great passenger

Artie prefers to be someone’s one and only (he likes to chase small critters, and while he’s met other dogs and goes for partner walks with them- he just doesn’t know how to play with them), he definitely has more than enough love and personality to brighten up your life and home.

If interested in meeting Artemis please email adoption@sdsanctuary.com.

GAINESVILLE, TEXAS: NEED FOSTER or ADOPT

Libby is a 2 yo spayed female Anatolian Shepherd, 100 pounds, HW neg, fully vetted.  

This girl is super sweet and friendly. Looking for either a foster or adoptive home. 
Libby is going to be a big girl when she finishes filling out. She weighs 100 right now and is still underweight.

Miss Libby is going to do best with an owner who has experience with Anatolians or another flock guardian breed.  She is everything you would expect from an Anatolian... watchful, protective, alert, athletic and intelligent.   Libby is still rather puppyish and energetic so she is going to do best in a home with a secure fence and maybe a playmate such as a large male dog.

Transport assistance may be available within 1000 miles, depending on where you live and the availability of volunteer drivers.

animal.description: Lady is a lovely 9-year-old mixed-breed girl who currently weighs about 58 pounds. She came to SFAS when her owner could no longer care for her. Lady is so well-named - she is a delight to spend time with and she is excellent on leash. Lady will politely accept all the attention she can get. Let's just say she would love to be the queen of the house. If you have another dog at home, we do ask you to please bring them in for a meet n greet during your appointment. Lady's adoption fee is paid for by Mrs. Vigil's class at Nino Otero Community School. She is spayed and microchipped and has age-appropriate vaccinations. A licensing/microchip fee may apply. To meet Lady or to be added to her waitlist, call (505) 983-4309 x 1610 and leave a voicemail message that includes the DOG'S NAME, plus YOUR NAME and A GOOD PHONE NUMBER - OR e-mail this information to adoption@sfhumanesociety.org. A scheduler will call you back within 48 hours to confirm your request. If you have other dogs at home, tell the scheduler you would like to bring them along for a Meet n' Greet. SFAS offers a variety of excellent training classes, seminars and Trainer Talks led by animal behavior professionals. These are half-price for animals adopted from any shelter or rescue group! Due to current COVID-19 restrictions, classes and talks are all presented virtually using Zoom. For course descriptions, schedules and registration, visit https://sfhumanesociety.org/our-programs/behavior-training/group-training-classes/ for classes and https://sfhumanesociety.org/our-programs/behavior-training/special-seminars-and-workshops/ for seminars and Trainer Talks.

animal.description:
Meet Tippy! When this beautiful girl came to us, she was pregnant and undersocialized. She moved in with her foster family, started to gain some weight and raised her sweet puppies. Now that her puppies have found their furever families, it is time for Tippy to find her furever home! Despite her rough start, Tippy has learned that people are great. She is incredibly sweet and loves attention. She especially loves belly rubs and brushing. Tippy had not spent a lot of time inside a house, so she will need someone who will help her perfect her house manners. Tippy has been with cats and ignores them, but would be best as an only dog so her family can focus on helping her be the princess she so deserves to be :)

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/adoptable-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed. 

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.

animal.description:
I'm a goofy, happy, playful little dude. I love to play with toys and snuggle. I walk nicely on a leash and also like to go for stroller rides. I'm a perfect gentleman on car rides too. I'm still a puppy and need help with potty training as I have never lived in a home before. I'm a distemper survivor! I have lasting symptoms from having distemper when I was a little pup. I have a rythmic tremor and my body is constantly in motion, even when I'm sleeping. I'm not in any pain and I don't require any medication. I have some difficulties using my back legs. I can still walk and run, I just drag my paws occasionally. I'm still a happy-go-lucky puppy and can do everything other dogs do! I would love a home to call my own where I am loved for all my special quirks. I may be good with other dogs, I just haven't met many. The rescue will help with dog introductions to determine if any potential furry family members could get along. Did I mention I make the cutest little grunty noises when I'm playing?! I will always have you smiling and laughing. I know you will love me once you meet me! Email Mayday today so we can start our happy life together!

If you or someone you know is interested in fostering or adopting, please visit our site at www.maydaypitbullrescue.org or send us an email at info@maydaypitbullrescue.org

animal.description:
**WE ONLY DO HOME VISITS FOR ADOPTIONS NEAR BROWARD & PALM BEACH COUNTIES**

Meet handsome Gus, a Chi-Pin/Chihuahua Miniature Pinscher who weighs in at 14 pounds with low-rider legs! LOL! His owner passed away and the family doesn't know his age, but our vet really thinks he is about 8-9 years old according to his full blood work and exam. He is the sweetest and affectionate companion. He is a goofy guy that is easygoing and gets along with small calm dogs and adults, no cats or small children He loves to go on long walks and is happy just to be with you. Gus is a low rider, small with stubby legs, muscular, and a charming personality! He is friendly and loves to meet new people! He likes car rides and playing with his toys. He is house trained and signals when he needs to go out. He sticks to you like glue, happy, and kissy. He is a goofy guy and will steal your heart. He is healthy and wagging his nubby tail for your attention. Gus has his bags packed and is waiting for his forever family to come and take him home. If you are interested, please fill out the adoption application. This dog's adoption fee is $350 to go towards their vetting (vaccines, spay/neuter, heartworm/Ehrlichia/Lyme test, fecal test, pre-op blood work, dental cleaning, and microchip as well as grooming if needed). If you are interested please fill out the adoption application For additional information regarding our adoption process, please check our FAQ's Page. 

All dogs in the care of Get a Life Pet Rescue live in loving foster homes while waiting for their perfect match. They don't live in cages or crates (unless there is a medical reason to do so.) They are treated as family pets while in our care. * All dogs in our care are fed premium brand holistic food as well as supplements and vitamins specific to each dog's needs. We don't buy inexpensive bulk dry kibble, our rescues are fed premium wet food diets as part of a comprehensive rehabilitation program to ensure maximum health.*All of our rescues receive complete quality vetting including full dental cleaning with pre-op bloodwork, spay/neuter, vaccines, and grooming. Dogs in need of specialized medicine will be seen by specialists, such as full cardiac workups, ophthalmologist visits, all suspicious lumps, and bumps are biopsied, and every medical need is transparent to potential adopters. *Once you adopt from Get a Life Pet Rescue, you become part of our compassionate family and we are here for you if a problem with your precious dog arises.

animal.description:
Finn is a laid back, gentle giant. His favorite thing is to lie on his bed, eat and watch old cartoons (Bugs Bunny, Daffy Duck and commercials) on TV :) He often sleeps with his sleeping bag which he gets under or inside. He is very gentle and slow taking food from your hand. He eats slowly, is not in any hurry and doesn’t want to be bothered while he eats or share his food. Finn loves car rides and visiting folks, especially going to Lowes lumber and garden sections - he's never met a stranger and loves the attention! He walks great on a leash and is very attentive. Finn does not like small 'barky' dogs and may engage a cat, but he is great with other dogs. Finn is totally house trained and is the perfect house guest. He has never been in a crate (doesn't like them and doesn't need one). He doesn’t require a lot of activity but does enjoy walks and interaction outside as well as inside. He will require a secure fenced yard but prefers being inside when it's cold. Finn has been good with children over 8 years of age. He had to have his coat shaved off due to severe matting but it's growing back nicely and he's looking good! He’s very patient, listens, takes direction quickly and is eager to do things and learn. He doesn’t bark unless he needs to go out or something is outside. Finn's hearing was poor due to a chronic ear infection but has improved tremendously. His foster says that Finn is very loving, gentle and precious and his new family will be very happy to have him as their pyrfect addition!

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
NGPR dogs are in foster homes throughout the U.S., NOT Beacon, NY. View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/adoptable-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed.

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.

animal.description:
If interested, please

complete the

Adoption Application

on our website at

www.NeedyPaws.org

and we will contact you.

Adopters must live within an hour's drive of St. Louis, MO.

Our $250 adoption fee includes up-to-date vaccinations, heartworm testing and preventative, spay/neuter and microchip.

NO APTS/CONDOS

6FT FENCE REQUIRED

NO SMALL CHILDREN

Hi! My name is Bowser, and I'm a 7-month old, happy-go-lucky Husky mix. My foster Mom says I'm a confident, ENERGETIC boy that loves to PLAY! I would run and play all day long if I could!!

I also love playing with toys and chewing on nylabones, but I really love running through the back yard with my 4-legged foster siblings. I would do best with another young, playful dog in the home to continue teaching me how to become the best dog I can be! I'm a young buck with a ton of energy to burn and will need a fenced back yard in my forever home. And I can jump really high so a 6 foot fence would be ideal.

Did I mention that I love to play!?! But what I love most is SNUGGLING. And I only weigh 35-40lbs... perfect snuggling weight!

I may accidentally knock down little humans, but I don't mean to and I'm learning to take it down a notch when I come inside. I can also be a little mouthy when playing, so I would do best without very young children in the home as I'm still learning what is appropriate to chew on. I don't mind being kenneled at night... it keeps me from exploring and finding new things to chew on. And I haven't had ANY accidents in my crate!

I would love to become the newest member of a family that will include me in their activities. If you like snuggling after going on new adventures together, fill out an application and my foster Mom will contact you so we can meet!

We are a 100% foster-based rescue and all of our dogs live in approved foster homes. We are dedicated to finding the best Forever Homes, and will perform home visits and conduct veterinarian and reference checks for each potential adopter.

animal.description:
Looking into Calvin's eyes --- does your heart just break for him? You can just tell how sad and confused and lost he must be. This sweet, 2 year old boy came to us as a stray in November 2020, after being found by the police. He is a nervous dog, seemingly not knowing what to do with toys, or attention. If we had to guess, he probably spent most of his time alone, perhaps outside, and under-socialized with people. Calvin is friendly with other dogs and enjoys meeting them, although he probably doesn't know how to play yet. Sadly, Calvin was adopted and after one day, not nearly enough time to adjust into his new environment with new people, he was returned to us. Thankfully he is back with us now and is ready for his actually true, forever, loving home. Calvin is looking for a household with adults only. Calvin may be placed with another dog thats respectful and no cats. 

If you are interested in learning more, please contact our placement team:

animal.description:
**Please read Pepper's entire profile, which includes a link to the adoption application. Thank you!** 

Meet Pepper, a 2-3 year old, 56 pound Lab/Hound/Boxer mix lady. 

Pepper was found under porch on while having her puppies. As soon as she was through labor rescuers brought her and her puppies to a safe and loving foster home. The puppies all went home and Pepper is looking for a family of her own.

Peppers foster wanted to share this about her:
Pepper is an affectionate girl, loves attention, particularly belly rubs, and is very sweet. She will follow you everywhere and lie at your feet.  She is a wonderful companion.  Her tail is always wagging, and she loves to play. She is housebroken and loves to sleep at the end of your bed or on the couch at night.  She gets very excited when going on car rides and enjoys walks in the woods or playing fetch in the yard.  As an older rescue, Pepper is leash reactive; pulling hard to investigate other dogs so she is best if she can find a home where she can continue to work on changing this behavior.  We see her as a suburban dog where she can have a fenced in yard to play and can enjoy peaceful walks. She loves people and she is smart.  She is now following all commands of sit, stay, up, down, this way, leave it, off, come, heel, touch, fetch, drop it. When she wants to play, she will nudge you to let you know. As a young rescue, she can get a little over excited and mouthy; and may chew on soft items unless redirected to her toys. She loves tug-a-war and cuddles on the couch and will snuggle up beside you and sleep. Pepper should not be in a home with other dogs or cats but is great with kids. My son says she is the best, most fun foster dog we have had!

Pepper is ready to be somebody's special pup!

Pepper is good with children but since she takes time to adjust she can only go to a home with older (teen +) dog savvy children.   She would not be a good dog for a child's first dog.

All dogs are up to date on vaccinations and spayed/neutered at the time of adoption. All dogs require professional training to become the best family member they can be.

Pepper has finished heart worm treatment. She will need a blood test re-check in six months which can be done at the expense of the rescue if at our veterinarian.
To adopt or learn more about Pepper, you must fill out an adoption application. To find the application, copy and paste this URL into your browser: WWW.GDRNE.COM/ADOPTION-APPLICATION [Adoption Fee: $495]  **  PLEASE READ: If a dog is listed, then s/he is currently available for adoption. Their information is correct to the best of our abilities and the information we have been given as of the day of posting. Please note, GDRNE does not guarantee the breed of any dog or puppy unless stated that we have run DNA. All breeds listed are educated estimates. Our dogs are rescued from various situations. It is most likely that both their parents were strays and even if not, mixes of some sort and that their grandparents were mixes as well. The dog may have some genetic material of an American Staffordshire Terrier (pit bull). The dogs are usually mixes of many breeds, making them a breed all their own - a True and adorable American MUTT. If you are interested in this dog, you must submit an application. Great Dog is not a shelter so there is no building you can visit. Our dogs live in private foster homes until adopted. To learn more about our *shelterless* rescue, adoption fees, and procedures, review the list of Frequently Asked Questions on our website at WWW.GDRNE.COM.

animal.description:
Date of birth: 5/2019

12/1/2020:  Reuben is a super cute Lab/Boxer mix!  He has sweet button eyes and a beautiful coat. He’s long legged.  He currently weighs 50 lbs but should gain some weight.  He’s 1 1/2 years old.

• Reuben is very friendly and playful.  He loves playing with toys!  

• He’ll need a fenced yard. He’s got a lot of energy! 

• We would also like Reuben to have a doggie friend in his new home. He gets along well with other playful dogs his size. He loves playing in the yard with other dogs and it’s a great way for him to run off some energy. You could bring your dog to meet Reuben to see if they could buddies.  
 
• Reuben is too rambunctious for a home with young children at this point. He jumps up quite a lot and is very much a big active puppy!  He’ll need work on basic manners. He is very food motivated so should do well with training and be an eager learner.

•  He keeps his kennel clean.

• Sadly, Reuben tested positive for heartworms.  He will get his first heartworm treatment on January 11.  He’ll need to be restricted to limited activity at that point and for several weeks. The treatment is done in our clinic and the costs are covered. We can fill you in more about his heartworm treatment and what that entails if you are interested in adopting or fostering Reuben.

• Reuben has been neutered, vaccinated and microchipped. He’ll be a fun companion if you’re looking for a happy and playful companion for yourself and your dog!  He was originally in a shelter in Arkansas and his time was up there, so we transferred him and some of his shelter buddies up here to find homes. 

MORE ON ADOPTING OUR DOGS... 

> COVID-19 UPDATE:  PLEASE SUBMIT AN ONLINE ADOPTION APPLICATION AND A MEMBER OF OUR ADOPTIONS TEAM WILL REACH OUT TO YOU.  Please visit our web site at HSGKC.ORG for an adoption application, our current COVID-19 adoption protocol, and other adoption info. 

> If you decide you'd like to adopt one of the pets you meet, we reserve the pet for you but we generally don't send the pet home with you that day. We’ll instead schedule a pick up date and time that’s convenient for you.   

> Our goal is to send you home with a healthy pet and any information and support you may need to help your new pet adjust to his or her new home.  All of our dogs & puppies have been spayed or neutered, vaccinated, microchipped, dewormed, treated for fleas & ticks, tested for heartworms (7 mo. and over), and are on monthly heartworm preventative. Puppies who are too young to receive all the necessary puppy boosters and/or first rabies shot may be brought back to us for those vaccines at no extra charge. You will also receive a leash, collar, coupons for pet supplies and services, toys, and educational materials. And we'll give your dog a bath before he or she goes home! 

> Please note that we prefer and may require a fenced yard for many of our dogs.  Exceptions are made on an individual basis depending on the dog's needs, the person's dog experience, the dog's and person's activity levels, home environment and other factors. 

Thank you for searching for a shelter pet!

Dog Adoption Contact Info:
Email: christine@hsgkc.org
Phone: 913.521.2339

animal.description:
Breed: Labrador Retriever/German Shorthair Pointer mix
Sex: Neutered Male
DOB: ~10/02/2017
Weight: 55 lbs
Energy Level: Medium-High
Personality Type: Affectionate, Energetic, Playful
History: Transferred from another shelter 
Good With: Teenagers and up!
Fence Requirements: Preferred
Ideal Home: No apartments. Active home.
Special Info:

The information we are providing for this animal was developed based on observations and assessments in a shelter or foster environment. We do our best to provide information that will help determine if the dog might be a good fit for you. Please note that behaviors may change in a home environment. We also ask our applicants to assume that any animal they adopt from us will need to be potty trained and learn house manners, although this is not always the case. Our online animal bios are designed to provide as much information as possible and answer some anticipated questions. We do not have the resources to respond to emails with more specific questions.

We are receiving an unusually high number of applications per pet at this time! Please follow the rules below to ensure your application is reviewed; pay attention closely to these instructions because applications will NOT be processed if they are not followed. Please keep in mind that dog/cat availability is currently changing by the hour; you will receive an email if the animal you are interested in is no longer available. New dogs become available almost every day, so feel free to let us know if someone else interests you if your initial choice is already adopted! 

Fill out the application (DOG: https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/IHD-DOG-Application-9-10-18.pdf, CAT: https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/IHD-CAT-Application.pdf) completely. Every question must be answered, and it must be signed. If you are going to type your responses, open the application, save it, type your answers, and save it again. 

-Applicants must be 21+ years old and live within a 50-mile radius of our shelter at 22415 Groesbeck Hwy, Warren 48089.

-You must identify at least 1 dog/cat that you are interested in. If there are multiple dogs/cats, number them in order of priority. 

-Scan a copy of proof of home ownership (i.e. tax bill, deed, or mortgage payment - you can black out the account #, etc.) or animal clause/agreement of your rental agreement.

-Attach the application and home ownership proof/rental agreement animal clause to a new email and send it to bark@iheartdogs.org. The subject line must be formatted to read ""#1 choice of dog/cat, Your First and Last Name"". Example: Subject: Fido, Jane Doe
Once your application is received, it will be assigned to an Adoption Counselor who will follow-up with the applicant who is the best fit within a few days, or to discuss other dogs/cats. It could take up to a couple of weeks for you to receive a final disposition on your application so there is no need to check on the status.

-Introductions will be scheduled by appointment only, 45 minutes per appointment. The entire household, including current dogs, must be present for the appointment. The introductions will take place outside in our parking lot.

-We will continue to perform vet checks for current and prior pets in the household.

-Home visits will be in person for the yard and virtual for inside the home.

-Finalizing the adoption will also be scheduled by appointment.

While this process may seem cumbersome, it is interim during COVID-19, and it is designed to help us respond to the volume of emails we receive every day. Since we are receiving a high volume of applications, please be patient if a dog/cat is no longer available. 

Thank you for your understanding.

animal.description:
Meet Lincoln
This handsome boy, Lincoln, was rescued from a high kill shelter. We brought him to the safety of our shelter as we search for his forever home.
Lincoln is nine month old Labrador retriever mix. He’s medium size, weighing 54 lbs.  He’s a super sweet boy who is finding it hard to be at the shelter. The noise and confinement of the shelter environment have increased his anxiety. Luckily we have wonderful staff who understand this and are working with Lincoln to help him adjust. He has a lot of energy that needs to be channeled. Outside of the shelter, this boy is a terrific dog. He’s smart, sweet, and so much fun. He’s much calmer and can focus better. Lincoln is very sensitive and just wants to belong to someone. Someone who can work with him patiently and give him the security and safety he’s lacked his whole life. He is smart and learns quickly. He will make for a great hiking buddy. We don’t yet know how he’ll respond to other dogs or cats and can test for potential adopters. 
Lincoln has a lot of potential and just needs to be out of the shelter for his true personality to shine through. He’s loyal and earnest and tries so hard. If you are able to open your heart and home to a sweet young dog who will make for a wonderful companion, handsome Lincoln may just be the one. 
Call 706-865-4135 for information on additional health services provided as part of the adoption fee.  If interested in one of our puppies or dogs, please submit an application online or at the shelter. Applications can be submitted online at: https://www.charlessmithgallhumanesociety.org/page/dog-adoption-application 
Once an application is submitted online, you will receive an email saying your application has been successfully submitted.  If you don’t receive this email within 24 hours, please check to make sure all application fields were completed or please call our shelter at 706-865-4135. All adopters must complete an approval process which involves a reference check with current/recent vet and a brief home visit if located in the immediate area. We do permit out of state adoptions. Adopters MUST come to the shelter to transport their new family member home. We do not ship nor do we transport them to their new homes. Adoption policies and application procedures are detailed at the shelter website: http://smithgallhumanesociety.org/ under tab All Adoptable Animals.
Charles Smithgall Humane Society (CSHS) is a No kill shelter. Animals in our care remain safe with us until adopted. Resident animals are primarily owner relinquished and also accepted from local Animal Control. The facility usually is operating at capacity with a list of animals waiting for space to open.
Adoptions and meet and greets are being scheduled by appointment only. Please call our office, email us or complete an application and someone will be in touch just as soon as they can. 
Location: 4823 Helen Hwy., Sautee, GA 30571, Phone: 706-865-4135
Email: smithgallhumanesociety@windstream.net
Our shelter in Sautee GA is located about 3 miles south of the alpine town of Helen in northeast GA.

animal.description: This face is as close to perfectly symmetrical as can be and, besides, that he's super gorgeous with that muscular black and white body and those long legs. Charlie is a pretty classy one-year-old, thirty-five-pound Terrier/Mix who is ready and willing to find his new people. Charlie is halfway through puppyhood and somewhere along the way has already earned some inside manners and it won't take much to help him understand your rules and for you to become familiar with his way of communicating. A quick obedience class and boundaries with everyone on the same page and you'll be good to go. Talk about a great time for a dog. This active and intelligent guy is going to be the hit of your neighborhood on your outings. Winter is coming and Charlie would love to help you get through the wintertime blues. Seriously, Charlie is exactly what the doctor ordered. Charlie has a placement restrictions of someone who knows how to read dogs when doing introductions and he would do better with no kids or older kids, and you are going to fall in love the minute you meet him. Charlie is a medium boy and he does need to be exercised so please keep that in mind. Charlie is up to date on all of his vaccinations, is neutered, and will be microchipped and whoever is lucky enough to adopt him is going to have a friend for life. For more information about our policies and answers to questions you might have please visit https://www.newpawsibilities.com/26425-2/

animal.description:
Ruby is an 8 year old, 13 pound, female, terrier mix. Ruby is a big personality wrapped up in a small package. After living her whole life rather solitary with a single owner who passed away, Ruby needs to take her time meeting new people. She is very cautious and protective of herself to strangers, but give her some time, patience, and TLC and you will have the snuggliest little friend to share your bed with.


Ruby was surrendered when her owner passed away from Cancer. It was a hard
transition for her to move from the life she once knew. Now that she has
settled into her foster home, she is doing incredibly well. She is such a goofy
and affectionate girl. She is a calmer dog overall, as she just loves to
snuggle with you on a couch watching TV. But she also loves her walks. For how
calm she is normally, she’s surprisingly athletic as well, so she would be up
for just about any adventure! 

 
Ruby is looking for an experienced owner, possibly one who has experience with terriers. Ruby will need someone who can help her come out of her shell and who has the confidence to get her through the adjustment period. Ruby will reward her future owner for committing to her care with tons of love and kisses once she gets comfortable. As mentioned, Ruby is extremely affectionate once she trusts you! And Ruby gets along well with other dogs and cats too! But, she is a typical terrier and would love all the attention to herself as well. If you think you have what it takes to be a confident owner and caretaker for Ruby, submit your application today!

Ruby is up to date on her vaccinations and is spayed. Experienced dog owner only with no young children living in the home. 

For more information about her, please fill out an application at www.ALRcares.com and email Julie@alrcares.com. We schedule meet and greets for approved adopters only, an application is the first step in our approval process. Thank you!

animal.description:
For my Petfinder.com friends, please contact the Shelter at (248) 858-1070 for more information. My Adoption id number is 315504.

I AM AVAILABLE FOR ADOPTION, HOWEVER DUE TO MY BREED MY ADOPTION WILL HAVE TO BE FACILITATED THROUGH A RESCUE ORGANIZATION. PLEASE SEE THE FRONT DESK STAFF FOR MORE INFORMATION.

This is Gilbert! He's a fun puppy that would go best to somebody that has enough extra time to work with him on training and obedience. In our experience he can be a bit mouthy when he's playing which is a bad habit that can be redirected to something productive such as a very durable toy. Gilbert is also very interested in being a lap dog which should be discouraged if you're not into that kind of thing. Overall Gilbert is adorable and would love to find his forever home very soon so he can start being a big boy dog in the real world! 

Dog relationships can be just as complex and complicated as human relationships at times. We recommend separating any new additions in the home while unsupervised until a comfortable relationship has been established.

American Pit Bulls are a misunderstood breed; for this reason, we implore adopters to these beautiful dogs to be very vigilant in training and socialization. This breed is very energetic and will need daily exercise. Because of their strength and energy, apartment living may not be the best fit. This breed can be loving, loyal and very smart. 

The above behaviors and personality traits have been observed while at the Shelter. If this animal was relinquished, information is gathered from the owner regarding behavior. Our wonderful volunteers spend time with these animals and give input on behaviors and traits. However, this description may not be all inclusive to how this animal will act in a loving forever home. Introduction to established family pets should be slow and monitored always. The same goes for children and other family members. Adopting a pet is a big decision and should be thoughtful. We suggest researching different breeds to match traits and personalities to your lifestyle. When adopting a pet, please know that this pet will be with you for their lifetime; patience and consistency will make for a successful adoption.
 Primary Color: Black Secondary Color: White Weight: 62lbs Age: 3yrs 6mths 2wks Animal has been Neutered

animal.description:
“Lookin’ sharp and lookin’ for love.”  There is no need to spend a fortune on fancy suits, I came into this world as a natural “sharp dressed” pupparoo.  My name is Tux.  I am a 2 year old, 55 lbs, male Lab mix.  The house training stuff was no big deal and I mastered it quickly.  I am a master of  crate training. While most of the time you’ll find me lounging as close to you as possible soaking up all the belly rubs, I’ll often show you a more playful side.  I am a perfect gentleman while on the leash and would make a fantastic friend for someone looking to find a daytime (I'm not a big fan of night time runs) running partner.  I’ll be honest though, even with my fantastic leash skills, apartment or big rig life would just not be for me.  I could live with cats.  I am a recent graduate of the Pups for Parole training program and have learned a lot of new tricks!  I really would love to live with one special person to give me all the attention.  Too many humans in my home might be too much for me. Im all dressed up and ready to meet my forever human!

My adoption fee is $150 and includes my spay/neuter, vaccinations, wellness exam, heartworm test, and microchip! If you're interested in meeting/adopting me, please visit www.rescueonespringfield.com/our-adoption-process/adoption-application/ and fill out the form! We do adopt out of state with vet references and video home check. *Adopter is responsible for coming to get the dog and returning the dog if the adoption does not work out* 

Don't forget to LIKE us on Facebook!-www.facebook.com/rescueonespringfield

*Remember, dogs are pack animals. Because of this, Rescue One does not adopt to outdoor-only homes. Pets are family and are not disposable.  Please make sure that you are 100% committed to a pet before considering adding one to your home.

Poor little Juniper came into the shelter as a stray, in February 2018, after being found running loose on the streets. Thankfully, she is currently in a foster home and is doing amazing! She loves to lay out in the sun, and get love and attention from her foster mommy. Juniper makes the most loyal friend, is super smart (knows a tons of commands), is highly house trained, crate trained and is just a chill girl to hang out with. Juniper's ideal is home is with a single person household with no other pets. 

Juniper is only available to rescue groups, so if you are a rescue and would like more information: please email: rescue@tohmail.org

animal.description:
Wilma is one of the most interesting and affectionate dogs we have had the honor of spending time with, with looks to run the world. She is passionate, animated, charismatic, spicy & sweet and is a devoted companion like no other. When she locks her eyes in yours, hearts go boom and vulnerability takes a whole new meaning.

Wilma is seeking a family who understands the breed. Someone patient. Someone dog-savvy and committed to continue her training. Someone who understands behavior and boundaries. Someone looking to earn her trust and in turn have the greatest friend of a lifetime.

Wilma would prefer a home with a yard. To set her up for success, a home with older children (over 10) is preferred.

We love our girl with lilac-blue eyes, who with one look can make the past, present and future rush through your veins. Her brain is to use. Her beauty is to enchant. She yearns engagement. She strives for confidence and enjoys finding solace in a savvy leader. She has so much love to give and will no doubt be an incredible addition to her forever family.

To learn more about Wilma or to fill out an application http://www.nlolchicago.org/adoption-procedures-and-application

animal.description:
Cookie is a 6 year and a half year old Akita mix weighing in at just under 100 lbs. She is on a weight loss journey but don't be fooled by her size, she's all fluff! She came to us as a stray so her history is unknown. She has shown us that she is a super sweet girl who loves attention. She does not like other dogs however, so she would need a home where she can be the center of attention. She is very intelligent and a tendency to be a bit stubborn. She knows commands sit and shake. She loves long walks and to play fetch with her Kong, but she can't do that right now. She has a torn ACL and is set to have surgery to repair it so she can play again.

The surgery Cookie needs to repair her torn ACL is scheduled with Westview Veterinary Hospital on January 14th. She will need a foster home for her post surgery recovery and rehabilitation which will take 11-12 weeks. We require that this home have no other dogs or stairs. 

Cookie is currently available as foster to adopt. Her adoption fee is $150, this includes her spay, heartworm test, vaccines current, deworming, heartworm/flea prevention and micro chipped. Her dog license is also required to be purchased for Sandusky County residents at time of adoption, which is an additional $20.75. 

Please visit the shelter to meet him, we show dogs Monday through Friday 1-4:30pm and Saturday 1-3:30pm. Please note, we do not offer same day adoptions.Come and meet your new best friend today! The Humane Society of Sandusky County is open Monday -Friday 1pm - 5pm and Saturdays from 1pm - 4pm. Also, be sure to check us out on FaceBook!

animal.description:
Trevor is an adorable, petite, shy boy who we believe is a mix of Chinese Crested and possibly Chihuahua based on his appearance and temperament. He is very kind and sweet once he gets to know you but initially he is quite timid. He was found as a stray and his owners were never located. We are not sure of his history of course but we think possibly someone was not very kind to him and he may have lived in a fearful environment. Trevor is approximately 10 lbs. and is believed to be about 2 years old. He does well on a leash and in the car. Trevor is scared of children and would do best in a quiet home, perhaps with an older person or couple. 

Trevor requires minimal grooming but will need occasional nail trims. 

Like many of our rescued dogs, we are not sure how well house trained Trevor is. Frequent outings with lots of praise for doing his business outside will go a long way towards making sure his house training skills are tuned to perfection!

Trevor's adoption fee is $325

This fee includes at least one health exam at our veterinarian while in our care, altering, all vaccinations including rabies (as permitted by age), a pre-adoption professional grooming and a microchip with lifetime membership that never will cost you a fee. 
 All dogs also leave with a new collar and or harness and leash as well as a gift bag which includes among other things, a starter bag of the quality kibble that is being fed at the rescue.
Adoption fees also allow us the ability to put funds towards the next homeless or unwanted dog in need of rescue!
If you'd like to considered to for this adoption or any of our amazing rescues, please fill our the application with the help of this link. https://www.shelterluv.com/matchme/adopt/AZST/Dog.
We review each application carefully. Please understand that sometimes we get numerous applications for particular dogs and as a volunteer based rescue we do not always have the time to respond to each and every one. We do our best to choose the most suitable home for each dog based on their specific personality and needs. 

Due to Covid, our application review process has been taking longer. We will usually contact you within 1 week if we have chosen your application to set up a meet and greet. We appreciate all applicants and do our best to pair every dog and family for a successful and happy life.

Mumbles was rescued from an area where there is an abundance of homeless dogs, and not a lot of shelter space for them to go while they wait for their forever homes. Mumbles is a very sweet pup but does require a dog savvy owner.   Mumbles is still very much a puppy and is active, he can jump high so we do require applicants to have a fully fenced in yard that is at least 6ft.  Mumbles is dog selective so we are looking to place him in a home with no other dogs and he cannot go to dog parks due to his selective personality.    It would be great to have an adopter with breed experience but applicants must understand the heeler personality/ traits.  Mumbles loves his humans, loves to play and would love a home to cuddle up by your side after a nice run in the yard.

Mumbles is up to date on required vaccines, neutered, microchipped

Adoption fee: $375

To apply to adopt Mumbles, fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org/applications. 

**Meet and greets will not be scheduled without an approved application.**

-------------------------------------------------------
FAQs -- PLEASE READ ALL BEFORE EMAILING

**Please note that SNARR NE is a volunteer-based organization. While our volunteers will try to respond to you as quickly as possible, it is helpful if you review the following information about our adoption process before emailing:**

- LISTED BREED(S) & AGE: We are taking our best guess on age, breed, and size when fully grown, based on the puppy's/dog's physical appearance and what we might have learned about one or both parents depending on the situation. *NOTE* We rarely know a dog's exact age, nor are we able to tell the true or full breed mix of dogs as our information is limited most of the time. Because we often do not have access to medical records at the time that we are posting dogs to Petfinder, there are sometimes discrepancies between what is posted on Petfinder and what might be listed on a dog's medical records.

- SNARR'S ADOPTION PROCESS: The first step in adopting or meeting a SNARR dog/puppy is to fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org/applications. Once we receive your application, one of our adoption application processors will contact you, review our adoption process with you, and answer any additional questions you may have. **We do not go on a first-come-first-serve basis for adoptions, but on best fit for a family and most importantly the puppy or dog.**

- MEETING ADOPTABLE DOGS: Meet and greets will not be scheduled until after your adoption application has been fully processed by one of our adoption processors.

- APPLYING ONLINE: If you fill out an online application, please do so from a computer (not a mobile device), make sure you answer ALL the questions in as much detail as possible, and that you receive a confirmation email. If you do not receive a confirmation email, that means we did NOT receive your application.

- PUPPIES: We do suggest listing a 1st, 2nd and 3rd choice on your application if applying for a puppy with several litter mates.

- ADOPTION FEES:  $495 for puppies / $375 for adults. Adoption Fees for Seniors, Special Needs and Bonded Pairs vary

animal.description:
MEET PRIETA!!

Underdog Rescue does not physically have this dog in its possession.

To visit with this pup, please make an appointment here: https://mcaccappointments.as.me/adopt. NOTE: People who sign up for these appointments often no-show. We have been told that you can go to the shelter and tell them you are there to meet this particular dog. No walk-ins allowed between 12-3PM and the end of the day. Please request a supervisor for a long timer or at-risk dog. We hope your adoption process is smooth and full of happiness!

Prieta was surrendered by her owner along with two other dogs that lived in the same home; Bubby (A4314074) and Loba (A4314073). These three are really good friends and love each other but they are afraid of people they don't know. They were not leash trained even though they were in the home for over one year. They were probably back yard dogs that weren't trained and didn't socialize with people. Now they ended up at the shelter and are very scared. The behavior staff has been working with the three of them and they are improving. They are starting to learn to walk on a leash and they are very happy to see each other when they are brought to the play yard together. They are still wary of the behavior staff and don't solicit attention from them.

These dogs are going to need an adopter or rescue that can give them a quiet home and understands that it's going to take a lot of time and patience for them to warm up in their new home. They do not have to be adopted together but they may do better if they could stay together. They should not go to a home with small children. Meet Huck!

Huck is fully obedience trained on and off leash.  He is still very active and will require daily exercise no matter the weather.  He would make an excellent hiking buddy! He is excellent on leash, knows heel, sit, down, come, place, no, leave it, off and out. He is NOT a couch potato, but with proper exercise does lay down to chew on his antlers, benebones and even take naps.  He is approximately 110 lbs, neutered, up to date on vaccines, and takes monthly heartworm prevention.  He loves other dogs but can be intimidating to some other dogs as he is rather playful.  He has lived with dogs as small as 17 lbs.. Due to his size and ability to accidentally step on smaller dogs, other dogs in adopters home must be at least 15 lbs. He is very good with small dogs but if he was playing he may accidentally hurt a very small dog by stepping on them accidentally with his big paws.  He has never been with cats but can be cat tested if needed.  Because of his size and excitability we are requiring no kids under 16.  He does need a calm assertive handler as he does like to push his weight around.  He will require a physical fenced in yard (no exceptions). 

Adoption fee is $250.00. 
Adoption application & home visit required. 

If interested in Huck fill out an app on our website www.muttsinarutrescue.com

animal.description:
NOTE: This is a courtesy posting for another rescuer. Please do not contact ARRF, as we do not know this pet personally. To meet Denali, see the contact information below.

Hi, I’m Denali, and I am SO excited to be in a lovely foster home after wandering the streets of Bakersfield. I was lucky that some really nice people found me. I was pretty sick and overweight with open wounds and a terrible sunburn (I’m pale, folks – the shade is my friend) but even though I wasn’t feeling my best, I was so grateful to be taken care of by kind humans. I’m a 5-year-old cancer survivor who’s doing great after having several tumors removed. Oh, and I’m deaf but it’s no big deal. I see everything! I’ve been recovering in a foster home, losing weight thanks to a twice-daily thyroid supplement, growing lovely snow-white fur, and having regular spa days – such luxury! I’m the perfect petite size at 42 lbs., and honestly, I’m a completely different dog now! 

I’m hoping to find a compassionate adopter, or a forever foster family who will protect me from the sun’s harmful rays and help me to live my healthiest, happiest life. In return, I’ll be the most loving, affectionate doggy ever because once you’ve won my trust, I’m yours.

Okay, yes, I’m a little nervous around new people, a little insecure in new situations, but I’m always willing to try and to trust, even if it takes me a bit of time. I really need to be an only dog in a quiet home with low foot traffic, and if there are children, they need to be teenagers or older. A private yard with lots of shade would be wonderful! I’m crate trained and have good house manners. I’m so ready to find my forever home.

To meet me, please go to http://waggingdog.org/

animal.description:
Some time ago, working in tandem with another rescue, we posted Matthew looking for a foster or foster-to-adopt home from him. Since then, he has become officially an FFFR dog.

When he was brought to CT by another rescue, Matthew needed some guidance and training. Since then, he has been living with a foster-based trainer, and has made a huge amount of progress.

This boy is a puppy -- only about 10 months old. He is some mixture of herding breeds - not sure which breeds! - and he is totally adorable, and very smart!

Matthew loves the company of other dogs - he would love another dog in the home to play with.

He needs to live in an adult home, with people who have experience with herding breeds.

Matthew takes some time to get to know new people. Once that happens, he is a true cuddle-bug :)

He is an active puppy who will need daily physical exercise and mental exercise as well.

A fenced yard would be a big plus for Matthew.

We want to set him up for success, and will want to do several meet and greets prior to moving him to a home. If you would like to adopt, we will want to do a trial foster-to-adopt placement, to make sure the match is a good one for both Matthew and his new family.

Matthew is adorable, and a happy boy once he is comfortable with his people and environment.

PLEASE NOTE: To foster or foster-to-adopt Matthew, you will need to be located within the state of Connecticut.

To foster Matthew, or foster-to-adopt, please fill out the appropriate application at our website - https://www.furryfriendsct.org/foster-application

or

https://www.furryfriendsct.org/adoption-application

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please download and complete an Adoption Questionnaire from our website and email Dena at DenaE@k-9lifesavers.org

You can learn about the adoption process and find a Word, PDF and ONLINE version of the questionnaire by visiting: http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/howtoadopt/.

Dog's Name: Bunny

Estimated Breed : Lab Pit Mix

Approximate Age: 2 years

Approximate Weight: approx. 54 lbs

Currently Living at: Foster

Adoption Fee: $300

DOG'S DESCRIPTION

Bunny is a spunky sweetheart who loves to give hugs and sit in your lap. Bunny absolutely loves affection so even though she gets along with other dogs she doesn't want them around when getting attention so she would need some work when it comes to sharing a person. Bunny would be a great walking buddy, but also enjoys relaxing with you...as long as she is with you, she's good to go! She has not had a problem when her foster left her loose in the house and only played with her toys while he was away. She has been accident free for a few days now and is extremely smart and learns quickly. She listens well, learns quickly, and is eager to please. She will do best with an experienced adult only family that knows how to handle the big lap dog that can't contain all her love.

Your new pet will require a refresher in house-training. K-9 Lifesavers strongly recommends all new adopters enroll their new pet into obedience training. This provides for an easier transition into a new home, ensures the dog remains well socialized, and helps form a bond between the dog and the new family.

Adoption fees cover basic vetting, spay/neuter surgery (for dogs over 6 months old), rabies, distemper/parvo vaccinations, treatment for worms, heartworm testing, monthly heartworm prevention and monthly flea/tick prevention (while the animal is in our care), and transport costs from high-kill shelter. Please note that on average, K-9 Lifesavers spend significantly more on each dog than their adoption fee. Adoption fee for HW positive dog also covers heartworm treatment at our partner vets.

Foster Program: Foster homes provide for the temporary care of a rescue until the dog is placed into a loving, forever home. For more information on becoming a foster parent, and our Foster Program, visit http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/foster/ or email our Foster Coordinator at foster@k-9lifesavers.org

Sponsor Me! Make a tax-deductible donation today by visiting us at http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/donate/ . Donations help us offset boarding costs and additional medical treatment for those dogs who need it. K-9 Lifesavers receives NO federal funding and survive with your generous support!

For more information on K-9 Lifesavers, or to view a complete listing of all our Adoptable Dogs, visit our website at www.k-9lifesavers.org.

Please "like" our
Facebook Page
for the most current events and new dogs.

Thank you for considering a rescue dog!

animal.description:
Snoop was brought to the NYC Animal Care Centers as an owner surrender due to the owners moving and not being unable to bring him with them in October 2020.  Due to overcrowding at the shelter,  he was slated for Euthanasia.  

Snoop was going to lose his life for absolutely no reason.

Pound Hounds was able to save his life due to a foster stepping up.

While at the shelter he did well with the other dogs and was a shelter favorite amongst the volunteers.

SNOOP'S STATS:

Approx age:     10 YEARS OLD (THAT IS WHAT THE SHELTER THOUGHT BUT HE LOOKS & ACTS MORE LIKE   6-7 YERS OLD)    
60 lbs
House trained
Kids:  ?         11 OR OLD AND OVER; SNOOP GREW UP IN HIS PREVIOUS HOME WITH A 10-YEAR-OLD
CRATE TRAINED:  WHEN SNOOP FIRST CAME TO LIVE WITH ME I WOULD PUT HIM IN THE CRATE & CLOSE THE DOOR & HE WAS FINE.  THEN I REALIZED HE IS NOT DESTRUCTIVE SO I STARTED LEAVING THE CRATE DOOR OPEN SO HE JUST SLEEPS IN HIS CRATE WITH DOOR OPEN.
Good with dogs with proper introductions.  t
UTD on vaccinations and microchipped.

Here is what his foster mom has to say:

SNOOP LOVES HIS HUMAN & WILL FOLLOW YOU IN THE HOUSE.  HE LOVES WALKS & JUST WALKING IN THE YARD EXPLORING.  IF YOU GIVE HIM A TREAT & IT IS NOT HIS FAVORITE HE WILL NOT EAT IT & LOOK AT YOU WITH THOSE SOULFUL EYES, LIKE WHERE ARE THE DELICIOUS TREATS YOU GAVE ME YESTERDAY?!  SNOOP IS VERY LOW MAINTENANCE. 
 
THE ONLY ISSUE SNOOP HAS, IS HE WILL GRAB YOUR HAND IF YOU GIVE HIM A TREAT.  WE ARE WORKING ON THAT.

I LOVE THIS BOY!! HE SHOULD BE THE POSTER DOG FOR ALL DOGS.  HE IS LOW MAINTENANCE, WELL BEHAVED WHEN LEFT ALONE, NEVER HAS AN ACCIDENT IN THE HOME & VERY EASY GOING.  HE WILL BE A GREAT FAMILY DOG!! 

**** He hasn't been neutered due to his age.

animal.description:
*Not a candidate for service dog*
Nik is a 3-5 year old neutered Belgian Malinois/German Shepherd mix. Nik will require an adopter with experience with large, active dogs and some understanding of working with less than desirable behaviors. WTFR is a positive reinforcement rescue and seeks adopters that believe in the same training methodology.

Nik displays mouthing behaviors. When extremely excited or worked up, Nik may pinch or mouth a human. He does NOT break skin or leave any marks. He has improved greatly with increased, appropriate enrichment and stimulation. He is learning to get a toy to hold in his mouth when he is excited. Nik’s backstory is unclear, so we are not sure how this behavior came to be, however these behaviors are not aggressive, simply undesirable. (Nik is fostered by a CPDT-KA dog trainer who can assert that these behaviors are not aggressive.)

Nik is a mix of high energy breeds. He can settle down in the home and in his crate, however he will need more mental and physical stimulation than the average dog; meaning more than a few walks around the block. Nik likes playing with toys and fetch. He will seek to find toys tossed out of sight (preliminary test for search and rescue evaluation). He may have enough drive to do search and rescue or hobby sports if his adopter is interested, but at this time we don’t think his drive is extremely strong. 

Although not aggressive, Nik would not be a good match for a home with children. We believe Nik is good with other dogs from previous history and he has not shown any concerning behavior towards dogs in foster, but he still needs to be formally evaluated with dogs (we will update bio when completed).  

Nik is crate trained and seem house broken. He is neutered and will be up to date on vaccinations.
