animal.description:
Sadie has had a rough go of it in her 7 long years of life.  Sadie lived life in an outdoor pen, neighbors fed her for over 5 years when they moved in because she was skin and bones from her owners neglect.  Fast forward to today, and Sadie was relinquished to us and she is a very healthy weight, has a shiny black coat, and all the comforts of an inside home.  Due to Sadie's isolation, she is not animal friendly and can be reactive on the leash.  Sadie graduated from Unchained Melodies Reactive Dog Class and is manageable on a leash, but she is certainly not a dog that can interact with other animals.  

When Sadie came into rescue we noticed an prominent limp.  X-rays show that she has a luxating patella, basically her knew pops out of place.  Surgery was not recommended at her age and recovery time.  Medical management seems to be making Sadie very comfortable and she enjoys her walks around the neighborhood and on the trail.  
If you are willing to give a dog reactive dog all the comforts of home and spoil her to the end of her days, Sadie may be your girl! 

Fun Facts:

Age (best guess) - 7-8
Breed (best guess) - Pitbull/Lab
Current Weight - 47 lbs
Dog Friendly - No
Cat Friendly - No
Kid Friendly - yes
Potty Trained - yes
Crate Trained - yes
Leash Trained - yes

All of our adult dogs are current on vaccinations, de-wormed, heart worm tested, spayed/neutered, on monthly preventatives & micro chipped prior to adoption. 

*Adoption Fee is $200.00, No out of State Adoptions ,Virtual Home Visits 
 Required  

*We do not require fenced yards for all dogs, fenced yards are required based on a dogs needs. *No invisible fences.

If you would like to meet this dog, please fill out an adoption application at www.unchainedmelodies.org/adopt/

Thank you for adopting!

animal.description:
Meet Poet!

Poet was left in the night drop box at Animal Friends of the Valley after being found as a stray. He had a large ulcerated mass on his face near his ear. Fortunately, our vet was able to safely remove it. Poet is much more comfortable without the mass and because we started him on pain medication for his arthritis. He's feeling like a new man! Poet is approximately 13 years old and weighs 45 lbs. - a perfect midsize pup!

Poet seemed a little confused in the Frosted Faces play yard, so we were thrilled he got to go on a two-week Frosted Fling, and that they decided to foster him through adoption! As Poet settled in, his sweet personality began to emerge. He began to engage more with his Foster Family and their dog. Poet now greets his Foster Mom with a wagging tail as he comes inside from potty breaks, and recently, for the first time, he ran around excitedly after being let out of his crate! These are precious moments for a dog like Poet, and we know there more ahead when he's given time to settle into a Forever home. Here's what else we know about this gentle boy:

Poet's Fling Family helped him establish a successful potty routine that keeps him from having accidents. He goes out within 30 mins after eating, approximately every 4 hours after that, and 30 minutes before bedtime. Poet has a good appetite and shows no food aggression while he eats near the other dog in the home. He loves treats and adorably follows his Foster Mom into the kitchen to get one. Poet is low-key guy who enjoys slow walks with plenty of opportunities for sniffing.

Does Poet sounds like the perfect fit for the dog shaped spot in your heart? Apply to meet him: www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/apply

Visit us at Open House: Saturdays & Sundays, 10 am - 1 pm.

Learn more about our programs at www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/family. No adoption fees, and we help with medical costs!

Apply to become a family: www.frostedfacesfoundation.org/apply

Questions: adopt@frostedfacesfoundation.org

Updated: 2/2/21 KG

animal.description:
Hi, my name is Maple, and I am as sweet as pure maple syrup. I am a one year old, 32lb, beagle Australian cattle dog mix who cannot wait to meet you. My foster family calls me Maple Sue, and I know that it is me. I love people and my foster sister. I love to take walks, long and short, with my foster sister. My foster dad says that I am a dream to walk, no pulling at all. We play in the house and in the yard. Inside, I have found a stash of toys, and haven't met one yet that I don't like. I love to carry of of them onto the couch, and play with all of them.  Outside I like to play chase and wrestle with my foster sister, and I usually stop when she has had enough. I had a couple small accidents on the first day, but now my foster family takes me out a lot so no more. Plus, I am better at telling them that I need to go out. I am working on basic commands, and almost have sit under my belt, and picking up shake from watching my foster sister. I still need some work on keeping all four paws on the floor, but I'm just so excited!  I love other dogs, and really love people. I am more interested in the cats than they are in me, but I leave them be when I'm told. I haven't seen any little people yet, but I think I would love them, too. I go into my crate on my own sometimes just to relax, or for some me time. It sometimes takes a few minutes, but I always calm down and fall asleep. Because I'm so smart, love to please people, and love treats, my foster family thinks I'll be easy to train. Did I mention that I love people? I love to snuggle on the couch and give kisses to my foster family. I will stop when they tell me they have had enough, even though I have so much more. My foster family thinks I will be a great addition to an active family, maybe a fenced yard so I can run around, who would like an affectionate, smart and sweet Maple Sue.

If you would like to be considered as an adopter for one of our great dogs, please go to our website- www.luckymuttsrescue.org and submit an application. Our process includes landlord approval and vet checks. We try to get applications processed in a timely fashion. Inaccuracies and/or incomplete data will delay and possibly cancel your application from being processed, so please make sure that you include valid information and contact information. You will be contacted via email if there are concerns or questions. Once your application has been processed, you may be contacted by one of our volunteers to set up a home visit interview. After your home visit interview is completed, all of your information is reviewed. If your application is approved, you will be notified. Meet and greets with dogs are only set up with approved applicants, so if you want to meet a dog, it is vital that your home visit is completed and that your application is approved. Adoption fees generally are: 
$400+tax for puppies to 3 years old
$350+tax for ages 4-7
$250+tax for ages 8 and up
The adoption fee covers spay/neuter, up to date vaccinations, microchip, general deworming, heartworm test and prevention (if old enough) and veterinary inspection certificate. Breeds of dogs are best guesses and we don't guarantee any breed. Adopters are chosen by what situation will be best for the dog. Submitting an application for a particular dog does not guarantee that you will be the applicant chosen to adopt that dog. Lucky Mutts strives to match dogs to the best home and will work with your family to find a good match. Please remember that we are an organization that is completely run by volunteers, so please be patient as many of us work full time jobs, have families and also foster dogs. Thanks for wanting to adopt!

animal.description:
Meet River Dee ~  River Dee is thought to be about a year old .   He is just a bundle of love and wants to jump right  into your arms or lap.  River Dee is affectionate and full of kisses. A total big MUSH:)  He just loves everyone he meets....especially other dogs.  River Dee will flourish with structure and an owner with experience,  since he tends to  act  like a tiny puppy. He is crate trained and is happy to settle in his little den for the night or whenever seen fit.  He is good with other dogs and it is suggested that River Dee go to a home with children over the age of 12 years old, reason being his goofy energy, need for love, and not realizing he is not the size and weight of a chihuahua.  River Dee is at our adoption center waiting patiently for YOU.   River Dee would NOT do well in a home with cats.  This handsome boy will truly complete your family...PLEASE give him that chance! 

**PLEASE READ ALL BEFORE EMAILING**

If you are interested in adopting any of the puppies, our adoption fee is $495 ( puppies) $375 (adults) which includes transportation from the South and we do suggest putting a 1st, 2nd and 3rd choice on your application if applying for a puppy with several littermates.

**Please understand that we are a volunteer based organization. While our volunteers try to answer all emails/questions as quickly as possible, below please find answers to some of our most frequently asked questions. We ask that you please read these FAQ's to see if your question has already been answered before emailing additional questions:

- If a dog or puppy is listed on Petfinder, they are still available. Please do not email asking if they are still available. If a dog or puppy is still listed, then we are still accepting applications :-) We do not go on a first come first serve basis, but on best fit for the family and most importantly, the puppy or dog.

- We are taking our best guess on breed and size when fully-grown (or already an adult), based on the puppy's/dog’s physical appearance and what we might have learned about one or both parents depending on the situation. We rarely are able to tell the true or full breed mix of dogs as our information is limited most of the time. 

- Our dogs/puppies are either at our Adoption Center in Brewster, NY, in foster care, or are adopted straight from transport. An application is necessary to meet any dog/puppy. Often, dogs and puppies are spoken for before they arrive. Many people feel more comfortable with a meet and greet which we completely understand and respect, however please know you are taking a chance of that puppy/dog getting adopted by someone else before hand.

- The way to start the process for any dog or puppy is by filling out an application. Applications for foster or adoption can be found at www.snarrnortheast.org and by clicking either adopt or foster from the main menu. If you fill out an application, please make sure you answer all the questions in as much detail as possible and that you receive a confirmation email, otherwise we did NOT receive it.

animal.description:
This youngster is truly a firecracker and at just 9 months there is still plenty of time to enjoy all of her puppy antics.  Bindee greets each new day with unbridled enthusiasm and literally squeezes all that she can out of every waking hour.  She is around 35 lbs., has an easy to maintain hair coat, and a “can do” attitude.  Her perfect companion needs to be very active and intent on including her in the activities of the day.  She is very athletic and needs to be busy, I believe she would excel at agility, frisbee, or a running partner.  Bindee loves being outside and would adore a day on the boat, traveling in an RV, or hiking a challenging trail then snuggling up next to the campfire ready to do it all over the next day.  Bindee can be a bit sassy so consistent manners/obedience  will be a necessity.  She will need an age appropriate play partner, a sturdy fence, and no small children (not sure about cats).
So if you are looking for an excuse to be more active in 2021...Bindee is up for the challenge and won’t let you waste a moment of your day. So why not grab a leash, throw open the door, and together relish the abundance at of each new day!

animal.description:
Update:  Marley got some disappointing medical news and needs a very special understanding person to open their heart and home to him.   We learned when I know he was only a year old in his original home, he was hit by a car and had a broken pelvis and needed his tail amputated.  So he healed and was able to walk again, he does leak some urine likely due to nerve damage from the injury.  He will need someone to keep him clean and wear a belly band/diaper wrap.  This poor guy has been through a lot in his young life and we know he’s not an easy placement but it only takes that one special person to change his life... could it be you?  Email njwoof@cs.com to meet him.  


This 5 year old chiweenie (chi/doxie mix) is short on legs but long on quirks in true doxie fashion ? 

He was passed around a bit after his owner died and ended up in a shelter... he’s a very nervous insecure little dude but sweet once he bonds to his person and is accustomed to a calmer adult home.  He is nervous with strangers and thinks it’s his job to protect his chosen people so needs lower traffic home without close neighbors.  Marley failed his resource guarding test at the shelter, biting the fake hand (but really, does any doxie love having their stuff taken away!?) so his person should give him space and time to bond and practice trading him if you need to take something from him.  He came into the shelter with a skin infection that has already much improved with medicated baths and treatment, and he is hypothyroid and on inexpensive medication he takes easily in cheese!   He’s the size and shape of a standard doxie, about 18lbs.  

Marley is nervous around other dogs and about selective about his canine friends as well, although he’s starting to improve in his foster home and even started to play with a chihuahua friend!  So he may be able to live with the right dog pending a meet and slow introductions. 

We are hoping we can find a doxie-savvy person who will understand and appreciate him for who he is and love him unconditionally. 

Please email njwoof@cs.com to meet Marley

animal.description:
Don't let his resting grumpy face fool you, Albus is an excitable boy that is full affection and love. Anytime you walk over to him his tail immediately begins to wag and his face starts to smile! He is also very playful and loves to chase the waves or play with toys. Albus is a bog boy at 2 years old and 25kg and probably some type of Boxer mix with maybe some St Bernard based on his colouring. While Albus will need a bit of training this handsome boy is certainly worth the effort!

Albus was abandoned by his previous owners and left to fend for himself on the streets. He became very skinny and sickly and some kind neighbours that had been watching over him contacted us for help.

Despite his sad past Albus has a lot of love in his heart and is very excitable whenever he gets attention from his humans. Sometime his excitement means that he jumps up on you and mouths (but never very hard) so an owner that has experience correcting this would be beneficial so he can get endless cuddles and pets.

Albus is very good at listening to instructions and trying to do the right things so he only needs guidance to show him the way.

Something in his past has made Albus very nervous of new dogs that he meets while on leash, although he tends to be fine when greeting all the new dogs to our house when he is off leash. His reaction comes from fear and owners that can teach him how to behave and have the patience for him is essential. He is improving all the time and even goes to the dog park with over 20 other dogs but can not yet be off leash without constant and close supervision. We know that with the right owner he can be taught to no longer fear other dogs while on leash but it of course will take some time. Albus would be very happy to have a dog companion but adopters must know that they will have to facilitate a proper introduction for Albus so he knows he can trust his new pup sibling !

He is definitely a dog that is used to living alone but shows no signs of aggression to our other dogs in the house and very happily co exists with them. He even recently has started to play with one of our bigger females which has been a big step for Albus and we are hoping he will start to play more and more! Albus would likely try to hunt cats so he would prefer a home with no cats.
He has done quite well with kids both calm and excited, and was known as the "childrens dog" when he lived on the streets as he loved to play with kids, so we would be comfortable adopting him into a home with older dog savvy kids, over the age of we'd say 7 years old, and we will be firm on this solely because as we mentioned  he likes to be a little mouthy when he plays sometimes and we would hate for it to be seen as him being rough with a young child

We love this gorgeous and unique, grumpy faced boy and we know he will make his new family smile. If you think he is the right dog for you then please inquire with some info about yourself/ your home so we can see if we think this special boy could be the right match for you !

S.P.C.A. Albrecht Center For Animal Welfare
 Requirements for Adoption
1. Most of our dogs will require a fenced in yard to allow them to play safely outdoors.
2. If you have other pets in the home, you will need to provide proof of current rabies vaccines.
3. If you rent your home, we will need to verify that you have your landlord’s approval for the pet.
4. If you have other pets, we strongly encourage you to bring them to the shelter to meet the animal you wish to adopt first, to make sure everyone will get along.
The S.P.C.A. Albrecht Center for Animale Welfare adoption fees vary. Please call the shelter for each pet's adoption fee. 803-648-6863. Adoption fees include age-appropriate vaccinations, deworming, spay/neuter and microchip implantation and registration. Heartworm testing and treatment is also included for adult dogs. love

animal.description:
LAB- Sleek black coat with some white around the muzzle area.
SENIOR LAB- Est DOB: 2012
ARRIVAL:  July 7, 2020
HISTORY:  Eli had been languishing for months in a NC shelter and when the shelter closed due to Covid-19, Eli was quickly running out of options.  We spoke up for him before it was too late.

We are absolutely thrilled to formally introduce you to our amazing Eli!

These days Eli can’t seem to stop smiling, and here’s why: To say that 2020 has been a tough year for many of us would be an understatement, and Eli is no exception. Eli came to us from a shelter in North Carolina where he had been languishing for months. Due to COVID-19, that shelter closed, and Eli, stressed from shelter life, needed to get out. To make matters worse, Eli was sick with tick-related illnesses and heartworms. Things were looking bleak, and the shelter put out a call for help on his behalf. Eli’s luck changed dramatically when CFC spoke up for him and welcomed him to the sanctuary. When word spread of this new development, donations poured in from all over the U.S. to cover his medical treatment. After his mandatory rest and recuperation, Eli recently received a clean bill of health, and he is more than ready to embark on the next leg of his journey.

Eli is an older lab mix, but don’t let his adorable graying brows and beard fool you–he has plenty of energy and desire to go and do and play and go and do some more. Eli is a good-natured, gentle, friendly, and playful yet easy-going guy who loves people (and the treats they dole out!), going for walks, playing with toys of all kinds, and fetching tennis balls. When people approach his pen, he leans his whole body against the fencing to create maximum exposure for receiving pets. He loves to collect toys in the exercise arena and will gently hand them to you if you want to join in on the fun.

We’re hoping Eli’s year will continue on this positive trend and wind up much better than it started. He has one more obstacle to overcome: finding a home of his own! With his sweet temperament and playful demeanor, we think Eli would fit in well with just about any family situation–you name it, Eli’s your guy. If you have another dog, we’d be happy to set up a meet-and-greet to make sure everyone agrees it’s a good fit. Don’t wait! Contact Caring For Creatures now to set up a time to meet this special boy. You won’t be disappointed.

Staff Update Dec 2020: Eli is an eight year old lab mix who has been at CFC for the better part of a year. When I first started working as part of the animal care team, Eli was recovering from heartworm. He had to have indoor "quiet time" for most of the day and was clearly not feeling like himself! He has since made a full recovery and the difference is night and day. Eli has the energy of a much younger dog and gets excited whenever someone approaches his pen. Enter and he will likely reward you by wrapping his front legs around your waist. He loves visitors almost as much as he loves walks and loves walks almost as much as he loves food. He seems to get along well with other dogs and is a quick learner when it comes to training and cues. Eli is a happy, adaptable dog that would make a welcome addition to most homes, assuming he's given time to acclimate.

animal.description:
We met Sweet Spunky Shelby when we were bringing pig ears as a Christmas treat to a local shelter in NC. 

Shelby was being held on a cruelty case, but on top of that she had been born with a significant birth defect.  She was born without a tail and no anus, also known as atresia ani.   

You would never know it, because although Shelby was tiny, she was mighty.  If this defect was not corrected, she would eventually develop bladder and then kidney infections which could have killed her. 

So we stepped up, said Yes! to taking her into our rescue. 

Shelby’s birth defects were more significant than we knew, and she is now recovered after 3 surgeries to get her all straightened out and ready for her fairytale ending.  

Shelby has so much zest for life and a ton of love to give.   Which is exactly why this post might be one of the hardest to write. 

We are head over heels in love with this feisty lady. 

However, our home, while it’s been a perfect place for her to lay her head and recover and learn to love, it’s not her forever home because she needs more attention than we can provide.     She is living as a part time family member and that’s not the life I want for her.  She needs a special family who will love her fully and completely and is willing to allow her to be the only dog,  Trust me she has enough love to give to you!   

Shelby is crate trained and does not mess her crate.  She is working on house training and has made significant progress.  She walks well on a leash and adores playing fetch.  She is active and goofy and such a sweet baby.  Oh... She loves posing for the camera and lots of treats. 

Medically she requires canned GI food (the only residual side effect of her birth defect).   This helps her go potty without issue.  It will be very important to keep up with these things to keep her happy and healthy.  She is also on anti-anxiety meds which are very minimally priced per month (approx $25). 

While Shelby is mostly house trained, she does need someone who will be understanding if you don’t get her outside fast enough, because once she starts pooping it’s not possible to stop it (she has no sphincter). She will find a pee pad if you keep it in a routine spot.  Her new family will get lots of coaching from us (Grace and Linda) as We know her body rhythms, and routine will be important, and crating when you are not home so she doesn’t mess the floor. 

We will require lots of updates and “Auntie” status as this little girl stole our hearts. 

We know the right family is out there, but am willing to wait until that day arrives. 

We are officially posting Shelby for adoption.  As hard as it will be to have her leave us, she will always be part of the Tanner family, our commitment to her has been and always will be to do what is in her best interest. 

If you are interested in having Shelby join your family, please complete our adoption application at:
https://form.jotform.com/83613156425152

Please be advised that we will require a home visit and a in person meeting with you prior to adoption.    While Shelby is currently in DE, both Linda  and I are committed to whatever travel may be necessary in order to place her in the perfect home.

Please feel free to reach out to us with any questions you may have in regards to Shelby and her care.

animal.description:
Brawny is a sweet boy. He is 9 months old. Brawny is 80 to 90 pounds and still growing. He is energetic. He came from a loving home and with a sister- Blocky. He loves to play, whether with other dogs or with toys. As a puppy, he will need a home that gives him lots of activity, training, and attention. He might prefer a home where he would have a doggie pal.
He is neutered and has his rabies shot. He has one more set of puppy shots, due the 14th of January.
*Note that puppies are at the highest end of our prices.* Also note that we ask that new owners be able to be home often, at least at first, because of the time and attention that a new puppy needs.
Please find our applications and valuable information under 'Adopt a dog'* on our website: *www.beaglesandbuddies.com* and email your application to beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Let us know your preference of appointment day/time and which dogs you are interested in and we will do our best to accommodate and email you the closest appointment available. Please allow us up to a week to get back to you. Most appointments will be Friday-Sunday, 10 am - 2 pm, for an hour.
*Note bring any other dog/s and the entire family to your meet and greet at B&B.* A complimentary training manual is included with each adoption, authored by terristeuben.com. Check out her website - she is fabulous!
B&B is glad to be open during the pandemic. We know the value and comfort of a loving pet companion and are doing our best to help the dogs and folks who need them. We update our website daily and are always rescuing, vetting, rehabilitating, socializing.
* We are accepting applications for volunteers to spend time with our dogs, hang out, sing/read to the shy ones, walk/toss ball with those who go to the playgrounds; cleaning, office work, gardening, and building/repair projects! *

Are you my furrever family?

For further info on the adoption process, please visit our home page and check out the "Adopt a Dog" section, which has thorough instructions. All our dogs are spayed/neutered, microchipped, and

fully vaccinated before adoption; they have been wormed, bathed, socialized, walked daily and much loved; each adoptee leaves with a leash, collar, and all medical records.

Our prices are higher than the shelters' because we nurse the dogs through their illnesses and get them needed surgeries and dentals. We also spend time socializing. Furthermore, unlike shelters, rescues do not get financial aid from the government and must rely on donations, grants, and adoption fees. Our fees for adults start at $150 and go up to $750. The higher end is for our most in demand dogs, such as young beagles and other purebred dogs. The lower end is for dogs who have been here a while. For puppies, we may go beyond this and charge $1000. The good news is that, because rescues fall under the "charity" category, the fees for our dogs are officially donations and are therefore tax deductible. You can think of it as donating to a worthy cause and getting a dog in return!

Sponsor Me

Beagles & Buddies must find ways to raise money so we can continue saving dogs. Your tax-deductible donation keeps our rescue kennel operating!

Hours

Friday: 10 am to 3 pm

Saturday: 10 am to 3 pm

Sunday: 10 am to 3 pm

Monday: CLOSED

Tuesday: CLOSED

Wednesday: CLOSED

Thursday: CLOSED



Weekday appointments may be available. We are a small staff and do our best to accommodate your needs. **Note that during COVID, we are not holding open houses on any day. Please email us for an appointment and include your application (found on our website, beaglesandbuddies.com, under "Forms"). Most appointments will be Friday through Sunday, though other days may also be available. We usually schedule one appointment per hour. Allow 1-2 hours for your appointment. Please look at our website and make a list of one or more dogs that you would like to see.

Contacting Us

If you have a question about adopting, giving up a dog, boarding, or volunteering, please visit the appropriate tabs on our
home page.

For more specific questions, call 626-444-9664 (please leave a voicemail if no answer) or email at beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Note that
Emailing
is always preferred!

Thanks!

Please note: If you are viewing this profile anywhere other than Beagles & Buddies own website, you are not receiving full info. Visit info on pet here.

Good with kids: Yes

Fun Bio: Hi, my name is Prince! I'm a little aloof and just a beautiful pup! I'm crate trained, love to run around in the yard, know my name and come when you call me (for the most part). I also LOVE treats. I never knew there could be so much love in the world until I was given some treats!

We always recommend crate training, positive reinforcement training, exercise, playtime, and a regular schedule for potty breaks when bringing a new dog/puppy into your home. Adjustment takes time for both you and your new family member, so remember to be patient and enjoy this new and exciting time!
Included in the adoption fee are age appropriate vaccinations, heartworm testing, deworming, spay or neuter surgery, and microchip.

animal.description:
I'm Sioux, an 18 lb, 3 year old, terrier mix. I was caught by animal control when I was living in a field in Rosenberg, TX along with a bunch of older puppies that looked to be mine. I had been there for quite some time and people were feeding me, but no one could catch me or the babies. When we were finally caught, the nice people from the rescue came to get me and my babies, to help us get used to people.
My foster mom and dad have taken their time and been patient with me to get me to come out of my shell. Whoever adopts me needs to be patient as well, because it was pretty traumatic and scary to be raising a litter of puppies in a field!
I sleep all night on a dog bed and don't have accidents in the house. I will whine a bit when I need to go out. I go out to the fenced yard to do my but come right back in when I'm called. I'm not a fan of the leash and don't care to be picked up. I get along with all my foster brothers and sisters, big and small and am pretty submissive. A friendly, companion dog in the adopters house to show me the ropes, would be a big plus for me.
I am spayed, vaccinated, microchipped, and have tested heartworm negative. My adoption fee is $250. Click on Adopt A Dog at www.soca-fbc.org/adoptables to apply.

animal.description:
Adoption fee on this dog is $300.

Easton is a big, handsome male who is 2 to 3 years old and was found as a stray, so not much is known of his past.
		
He is a big, bouncy, and a bit mouthy waiting for the right handler to show him the ropes.  Easton is crate trained and working on his house manners. Easton is in a foster home with two large German Shepherds which he enjoys playing with.
		
He has some prey drive and he loves to chase, so no small animals for this boy.  Playing fetch is always fun with him as he will drop ball on command. This young boy is eager to please his person and is always at your feet or nearby. Being a young dog, he will require a good walk or run keeping him active and engaged with lots of socialization.
			
Easton may look elsewhere for stimulation so teaching him leash control and recall command is a must.

This dog is a Level 3. Please be sure you understand what a dog of this Level requires. Go to our home page for an explanation of the Dog Rating Levels.

For more information and to see when this dog will be attending an Adoption Day, please see our Dogs page on our main website at www.gcgsr.org. 

We operate within a reasonable driving distance from the Greater Sacramento area, the Central Valley down to Merced, and Lake Tahoe. A reasonable driving distance is determined by where one of our volunteers is willing to drive within our areas of service. That means we don't adopt out of our area, to Southern California, or Out of State. 


Thank you for visiting!

animal.description:
Mallory is a brindle pitty, who is around 3 years old and is 51lbs. She is fully house trained and good in the house. I Leave her free range in the house when I leave or baby gate her to the kitchen and she does not bother a thing.  
She is Good with other dogs. She sometimes wants to play rough and is vocal when playing, so it scares some dogs. She is in foster with 3 dogs that don't play and she does great with them.  She has now done great with really playful visiting dogs thst actually haven't been scared of her play growling. She plays really well when they play back.  I will not home her with another female pit or a female alpha that plays.  She needs a silly fun playmate or just someone chill that will nap with her. 
   She loves kids.  She has not lived with kids, but she loves visiting kids or seeing kids in public. She gets excited and will ditch me for a child, every time.  
Absolutely NO cats, or birds, or other critters like that. She goes bananas when she sees critters. She has done fine seeing Cows and horses. I can't tell if she is scared of them or just has no interest, but she does not react to them.  She is a sweet girl. She is fun and loves to play with toys and run but also likes to nap. She Loves to be under the covers and gives a good laugh when we see her burrowing. She would prefer to sleep in the bed, but does fine sleeping in my living room with the other dogs. 
She loves riding in the car and sometimes rides around with me at work all day. Loves water but not huge fan of the bath.  She is a bit grumpy when she is tired and likes to sleep through the night and is definitely not a morning dog. It takes a bit to encourage her to get out from under the blankets and get her day started. 
   She does fine with my 4ft fence.  She will need a fenced yard.  When she is off leash, not in a fence, she does not listen. She will follow her nose and keep on trotting. She is excellent on walks with a harness.
   She is spayed and up to date on vet care. $150 
Waverly Mo.
    
   There will be an application to fill out. 
  Please make sure bully breeds are allowed in your area before calling.

     Please call and leave a message or text Laura 660-641-5667

animal.description:
Looking for a calm, loving, and experienced "Chihuahua whisperer" for Chewey, a super cute  12 lb neutered male Chihuahua mix. He is approximately 5 yrs old and super super sweet, however he has a stubborn side and sometimes reacts by growling and/or trying to bite... especially when he is resting and comfortable and you need him to move or trying to get him in a crate.  90% of the time he is an angel but 10% of the time he turns into a beast and is not for an inexperienced dog person or household. He needs someone that understands him and his boundaries. 
Chewey is great with other dogs and enjoys playing with them and also loves playing with his favorite toys and hoarding tennis balls in his favorite bed. He is also great with a majority of people, he doesn't like some men, and has no problem with children although we will only allow him to go into a adult only home or one with dog experienced older children.

Chewey is also UTD on vaccines, heartworm negative and on monthly preventative, neutered and healthy but he does have allergies which requires him to see the vet regularly to get a shot to control them. He also has had recurring untreated ear infections before we rescued him so this led to growths in both ear canals that we had to have surgically removed. That helped a lot however he is, and always will be, prone to ear infections most likely due to his allergies so that is something that will always need to be monitored by you and your vet.

Chewey has had a horrible and painful past, due to raging ear infections, but he is super special and just like every other animal he deserves his perfect person and happily ever after.  If you think you could be that perfect special person for him please fill out an adoption application for consideration found at www.cubbyscrusade.org under forms.

animal.description:
Age: 11m
Gender: Male
Weight: 84lbs
Energy Level: Moderate to High
Overall Drive: Low to Moderate
Location: Kent, WA
Cats/small animals: NO

Gimlet is a wildly goofy young Malinois with an affinity for affection and a loving personality that will win almost anyone over! If he were a human, he’d be a party planner – always willing to do whatever he can to make sure everyone is having a good time. He’ll keep you laughing at all points during the day, and his sweet demeanor make him a dream to be around.

Gimlet is a very observant dog and always has his head on a swivel when outside of the home. He is a little wary of strangers and requires slow introductions that allow him time to get to know the person before they interact with him. Gimlet does best with female dogs and non-dominant males and needs close observation to ensure play with other dogs doesn’t escalate. He rides well in the car, does well with loud noises, and is fully crate trained. Not much correction is required with Gimlet, he responds to voice commands and light corrections on a prong collar only when necessary. He has nearly mastered basic obedience and is working on more advanced commands in his foster home. Gimlet will need to be muzzled at the veterinarian’s office and may require sedation for more advanced exams, however we expect this to improve as he is continuously socialized in his forever home.

Gimlet will thrive in a house with someone that has Malinois experience and is willing to enforce boundaries and routine as he continues to mature. He wants nothing more than to be a part of his handler’s life, and so will do best in a home where he can be included in most, if not all, activities. Gimlet is still young but may find certain sports enjoyable as his drive continues to build. Overall, this boy just wants someone who sees life the same way he does: a party just waiting to be enjoyed!

WEST COAST ADOPTIONS ONLY

Must have previous or current, purebred Malinois experience OR other high drive working breed experience

Our adoption process includes- completion of an application, followed by a telephone interview. If that goes well, we will arrange for a home visit.
Adoption Fee: $500.00. Transport along Interstate 5 (Bakersfield, CA to Bellingham, WA) is available but cost not included in adoption fee. 

Please visit www.woofproject.org and fill out an adoption application located here https://www.woofproject.org/application

I am 11 years young, and l am looking for my forever home.

Adoption Donation: $250

All dogs are microchipped, neutered, current on all vaccines, heartworm tested and started on Tri Heart Plus; Vectra 3D.

All household members and any dogs from the household need to be present at the time of the adoption.

Our website is always kept 100% up to date with who is currently available. As soon as animals are adopted, they are moved to the Adopted Pets page so if they are still listed on the Adoptable Dogs or Cats page, they are still available. So keep any eye on the site for any animals being added as available for adoption as new animals are added everyday! We would recommend if you haven’t done so already that you submit a general online adoption application with us so it is on file for when you are ready to come out and adopt. The adoption counselors will be able to show you many that would be a good fit for your family. Animal House Shelter can not guarantee breed or breed mix of our adoptable animals. The animals are posted on the website as a breed or breed mix based on their physical characteristics they most resemble. We also can not guarantee the ages of our adoptable animals or how large puppies will be when fully grown.

animal.description:
This young, silly boy is Max! He has the cutest curl in his tail, and his ears are simply adorable. Because of his young age, Max still has a lot of puppy in him and will need an experienced handler who can help him channel his energy in a 'pawsitive' way :) Max is quite a smart boy; he already knows a number of basic cues and is working on polishing his house manners in preparation for his furever home. This boy is eager to please, making training sessions fun for him and his people! Max is a very cooperative boy and will thrive with a handler who is dedicated to positive reinforcement training to help guide him as he matures. This young boy is fun and absolutely LOVES playing with other dogs - he hasn't met any dog he doesn't become immediate best friends with! Max is the most affectionate and loving boy we have around, and he is trying to get the title of "the most adorable lap dog" of the year. Max will thrive in an active family where his people are dedicated to be consistent with his training. He will definitely benefit from having a sibling who can show him the ropes and keep him company. This boy will no doubt bring years of love and endless kisses to his furever family!

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/adoptable-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed. 

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.

animal.description: There is not a dog in the world cuter than Brody. This little guy is about 4 years old and hasn't had the easiest life so far. Brody was found chained up in the yard of an abandoned house, but even with a rough past, he is one of the sweetest and most loyal boys in the world once he becomes comfortable with you. Understandably, Brody is timid and nervous at first, and he takes some time to warm up; once he does though, you can't help but fall in love. From what we have seen, Brody is a sweet boy, but he does need a patient person or adult only family willing to give him the time to decompress, feel comfortable and settle into his new surroundings. Brody is going to need consistent training to help him face his fears, and because of this, Brody needs an experienced adopter, preferably someone who has experience with or knowledge about fearful dogs. Although he has shown great improvement and has been enjoying meeting new people, Brody's training is going to be a long-term process, and he needs an adopter committed to helping him feel comfortable in all situations and committed to his ongoing training. Although Brody has not shown a negative reaction to other dogs, it would be best for him to be the only dog in the home since it seems, based on his wounds, that he has had traumatic experiences with dogs in the past. But with all of the love Brody has to give, you won't even need another dog! Aside from Brody's amazing personality, he has the most adorable little face and the perkiest ears in the world! We just cannot get enough of this cute boy. Introductions are by appointment only. We will contact you once your application is received. You can submit it through this link: https://www.sammyshope.org/dog-app

animal.description:
UPDATE 1/15/21: Maxx is scheduled for surgery to remove a polyp from his ear. Under anesthesia, when they got a good luck, they found that he has multiple tiny polyps that they were not able to remove. The vet felt this may be due to allergies although the rest of his body doesn’t look very allergic. We are seeking out holistic care which is no less expensive but will boost his immune system for better overall health and we are hoping that, kept with this regimen, the ears will not pose a problem in the future.  Maxx‘s new family must have a good relationship with their vet so that they can work together as a team. Unfortunately this is now considered a pre-existing condition and will not be covered by insurance. Maxx is well worth the extra effort and care!

MAXX is a 3 yr old Olde English Bulldogge. (see link for breed origins & info: https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Olde_English_Bulldogge#History). He was brought up in a family that was going through a divorce with lots of yelling and not enough time for the new puppy. Maxx is terribly shy and his first reaction is to retreat. He needs a family that will take things slow and get to know him on his own terms. Maxx has grown leaps and bounds with us - he has learned to trust a select few and now enjoys his walks in the park. He is a good boy who has excellent manners in the car, is housebroken & takes treats ever so gently. Maxx lived with kids age 10 and up but because of his flighty behavior and “work in progress” status, we feel he would do best in a quiet adult-only home. Maxx has not yet been cat tested but seems to do well with a calm female dog. He was the only dog in his former home and would be fine as the “only child“ so he could get all of the extra attention that he needs. Max will require several meet and greets before his eventual home visit in his new home so we would like to keep his adoption relatively local, within comfortable driving range. Max has been neutered, vaccinated, microchipped and tested negative for heartworms. He has a polyp in his ear that is currently being treated. Adoption $250. Please fill out our adoption application at www.companimals.org if you are interested in starting the meet and greet process.

animal.description:
Chase – Anatolian Shepherd mix – 10 months – male (68 lbs.)

Meet our sweet boy, Chase! He was turned into a county shelter by his owner who said he didn’t have time for him. Really? Who wouldn’t make time for this adorable boy?? He’s with us now and is such a sweetheart. Chase is learning every day that people are safe and fun. His past owner obviously didn’t do much with him because everything seems like a new experience. Chase is now looking at new things as a bit scary… but is definitely relaxing more and more. He’s great with our volunteers and loves their company. We know he played a little with other dogs at county, but we’re going slow with him and other dogs. He seems interested, but unsure. We think with the right match, he’ll enjoy playing, but at this point he doesn’t have a dog-buddy just yet. Chase definitely prefers human buddies. We believe he’d prefer to be an only dog and get ALL the attention. We believe he’s housebroken because he’s had no accidents in his kennel. He’s also super affectionate and loves to be loved. Chase is active, but not hyper... we think he’d be good on hiking and camping trips. Remember, he is still a puppy and will need regular training and socialization to grow into a sound, well-rounded adult dog. If this handsome boy sounds like a good fit for your life, please fill out an application to meet Chase. 

https://form.jotform.com/91891552799173

Gorgeous Lucy wins our award for most likely to succeed!!

 Lucy came to us from Texas, shy, scared, and not ready to engage but how she has changed with love 

. From her lush clean coat and well-kept figure, it seems that she had a loving home once, and it's hard to fathom that she ended up on the streets, abandoned and unloved. It's taken her a while to trust people again, and a slow steady pace and soft voice win her friendship.

 Estimated at 1 year old, and weighing about 45 pounds, we let Lucy set the pace and she's nailing it! 

Lucy loves other dogs, wagging her tail, play bowing and ready to engage. She’s very tolerant with exuberant dogs, a rockstar!! A staff and volunteer favorite she has so much love to give. Lucy is a snuggler, happy cuddling on the couch when she's comfortable with her person. Lucy welcomes  play bowing and happy to be going for a walk and now approaches people in the home 

.She does best in a quiet environment both inside and outside the home; city life/busy streets are not for our girl. 

Would do well with another dog in the home  to keep her socialized 

 Lucy is spayed, up to date with appropriate vaccinations, microchipped, and ready to hunker down with her new person/family

animal.description:
We need to keep Rosy & Beto together!!  They are so completely devoted to each other.  Separating them would be devastating.  

Meet handsome Beto! Beto was surrendered with his sister Rosy when their owner could no longer care for them. These chunky monkeys do need to lose some weight as they were over fed and not exercised. They are currently on a low calorie diet at the shelter and getting walks every day. Beto is quite docile and compliant, he loves people. The only other dog for Beto is Rosy!  We wouldn't recommend this pair for a family with small children due to their size.


Rosy & Beto were lucky enough to be fostered over the holidays.  Here is what their foster parents had to say:

They were amazing!  Very loving and loyal.  Most of the time they would just curl up and sleep next to each other, otherwise they were following us around the house hoping to get kisses and loving.  They would curl up and lay at our feet or lay their heads on us while sitting on the bed.  They walked really well on a leash (except when seeing other dogs) and were always so excited to get out of the house and explore.  Surprisingly for how chunky they are, they weren't big beggars at mealtime.  They would noticed when it was mealtime, but didn't cry/bark/whine and eventually would just go lay down.  They definitely preferred when we were home, and would cry a bit when we went to bed or left the house, but then they would settle down.  They aren't very interested in toys but would chew on bones/a chew toy to calm themselves at night after we went to bed. Beto was nervous around new people and would look for solace behind one of us.  He would growl and bark, but it was clear he was looking for reassurance that the new people were ok to trust.  Overall, amazing dogs who just want to be loved and give lots of love back. 


FOLLOW THESE INSTRUCTIONS TO BE CONSIDERED: 

To adopt, complete the application at tarnj.org/adopt

If you have any questions at all, please DO NOT use the PetFinder inquiry form as we do not respond to those. Questions should be sent to info@tarnj.org. 

An application is required before any meets are scheduled so the best way to be considered is to apply ASAP at tarnj.org/adopt.

We are all volunteer-run and do our best to respond to every application. If there is a match with your application, you should hear from us within 2-5 days. If you do not hear from us, please check your Junk folder or email us for an update.

animal.description:
Dudley is enjoying his time with his foster family! After an almost too late offer to pull him, he was more than happy to walk out of the shelter! He came into his foster home to 3 dog foster siblings - and is doing great. He takes queues well while playing and gives them space when they ask. He enjoys chewing toys and bones - and has no problems with his people taking them away or moving them. He does get a little mouthy while playing - but his foster is working on correcting this with verbal commands and giving toys. 

He is working on house manners - sometimes he gets too excited but he calms down fairly quickly and corrects easily with a squirt from a water bottle. 

He has done well on walks - sometimes pullin at first but when he calms down from the initial excitement he stops pulling and walks very nicely. He has not had any accidents at his foster home in the house and does well in the back yard (which is only a 4 foot fence). He is kennel trained - he goes into his kennel if his fosters are gone during the day and at night for bedtime. He whines at first but when he realizes it is bedtime he calms down quickly and goes to sleep (this has been getting better the longer he has been with his foster). He is learning manners and tricks, already knows that he has to sit nicely for his food, and when he is getting his leash on. He knows basic commands such as sit, shake and lay down. He is a very smart, fast learning boy and likes to be where his people are. He will follow you around or whine a bit if he is blocked in another room. He has met several new people of all ages and has done great with them all (kids and adults). With a little bit of work and training this boy will make a great addition to any home!

animal.description:
Hello, everyone. Jackie here. I just arrived at rescue in November and am getting settled in.

My back story is one of love and comfort until love and comfort wasn’t an option anymore. My mom took very good care of me my whole life before she had to go through yucky, long medical treatment, and inevitably became too sick to take care of me as she wanted.

So here I am at the ranch, waiting for a second life of love and comfort with another mom or family.

I’m 10 years old and about 15 pounds. I’m UTD on all my shots and the vet (and everyone here) said, “She’s a super dog and someone will be very lucky to have her.” Do you feel lucky?

I’m selective about which dogs I like.   I’m also very much a Jack Russell and full of boundless energy, but I’m also wise and focused and know things these young four-legged whippersnappers haven’t figured out yet.

Come see me at

http://www.jackrusselladoptions.org/

animal.description:
Hello! Howdy! Hi! Hi! Hi! I’m Eddie and as you can probably tell just by looking at me, I’m a little silly man. I arrived at the rescue in fall of 2020 with a broken leg. Ouch! Doc put a pin in it, made me rest for what seemed like an eternity, and now I’m good as new … which is good … ’cause I’m new!

Yep, I’m a big ole puppy with a big ole puppy brain in need of some training and guidance. I’m not quite a year old yet, so life is all about quick naps between big ole spurts of relentless energy. Whee! And I’m a Terrier, so that’s 10x the normal puppy energy. Whee, whee!

I’m young, but I’m already a big boy at 20 lbs and they think I may teeter more towards 30 lbs. when it’s all said and done. But that’s just because I’m a “stocky” boy or “very solid,” as some people say.

So, if you have puppy know-how and a lot of energy, I may be the boy for you. I don’t come with an instruction manual, so I’m depending on you (or your dogs – I love other dogs!) to show me how to be a “good dog” when I’m grown. I guess I’m saying … don’t ask if I’m housebroken or have any manners yet because that’s a “no” on both. But I’m smart and learn quickly, so let’s gooooo!

Come see me at

http://www.jackrusselladoptions.org/

animal.description:
Looking to add some spice in your family equation?  Michael's your guy!  This fun-loving year and a half old Lab/Corgi mix will immediately bring a smile to your face.  Just look at him!!  At 45 pounds, Michael is compact enough to feel like a small dog, but the Lab in him brings out his super playful and sweet side.  Michael loves to take hikes and long walks and is particularly adept at backyard fetch.  When all the action is done, he is quite happy to chill out with his family.  As he is young, Michael still has a lot of puppy-like energy.  He would be very happy settling in with an active family with older kids who can play with him and keep him well exercised. Michael is housetrained and is just starting to understand commands.  He is very eager to keep working on learning more. 

Michael is looking for a family who can spend some time giving him loads of attention and playtime in return for endless love and licks!  


Thank you so much for your interest in adopting a dog from A New Chance Animal Rescue (https://anewchancear.org). We are a 501c3, tax deductible organization. ANCAR is a foster-based rescue, and we adopt within a 90 mile radius of Bedford Hills, NY.  You will find the adoption application here: (https://anewchancear.org/adopt/adoption-application/).  All fields on the application must be completed.
Please read about the adoption process (https://anewchancear.org/adopt/adoption-process/) so you'll know what to expect when you submit.   

Our dogs are in foster care and we do NOT have a shelter or boarding facility. AN APPLICATION MUST BE COMPLETED IN FULL AND APPROVED BEFORE A DOG CAN BE MET. This is a firm policy. Our busy volunteers are not able to respond to questions about the dog or dog meeting requests in the absence of an application.  We know these dogs very well because they are in foster care. Please read the profiles of the dog(s) you are interested in prior to submitting an application.  If there are specific requirements stated (ie: Fenced Yard or Canine Friend Required) these are included because they are vital to the happiness, health, safety and adoption success of that dog. 

We are only able to save as many dogs as we have foster homes (https://anewchancear.org/foster/faqs/) and resources for. We provide medical care including vaccinations, testing, deworming, spaying/neutering and microchipping before transporting our dogs. We provide all supplies, preventatives and any follow up vet care necessary while they are in foster care. These costs are high and the number of lives we can save is entirely dependent upon donations from people like you.  We do not receive funding from private foundations or government sources. If you can find room in your heart to help us, with any amount, we are truly grateful (https://anewchancear.org/help/donate/). We are a 501c3 organization, so all donations are tax-deductible. It is only through the kindness of supporters like you that we are 'changing lives...one tail at a time' by providing our dogs with 'A New Chance.' (https://anewchancear.org) 

Thanks so much.

animal.description:
Miss Molly is a 10-11 year old Yorkshire Terrier/Poodle cross (YorkiPoo) that was surrendered to our rescue when her senior owner entered hospice care. She is a tiny girl at only 8-9 pounds and has a soft coat of hair which requires routine grooming with hair cuts. This sweet little dog is quite timid initially of new people and other dogs, probably because she lived a very quiet life with her senior owner. Thankfully, over the past month, she has come out of her shell more in her foster home. Molly now lives with a few other small to medium sized dogs and she has started playing with them. She's not a big player with toys but does enjoy hanging out with the other dogs and with her foster mom.

Despite being so small, Molly does not like to be picked up nor held; she will actually shriek when picked-up; she's not in pain - it's fear. She does, however, enjoy laying with you on the couch or chair when she feels comfortable. Molly has a cute and funny way to let you know when she has to go outside, by stomping stomp her paws on the floor and barking while looking at you - so funny and cute. Molly will need an adopter willing and able to take her to the vet regularly for anal glad expression; she's had some anal gland issues which now need to be monitored. Because Miss Molly is initially timid, we feel she'd do best in an adult only household providing her a calmer environment in which she feels more comfortable. The ideal situation would be a senior person or couple.

This dog has been examined by a licensed veterinarian, provided inoculations, dewormed, tested for diseases, spayed and microchipped. ADOPTION APPLICATIONS are available by request from acaringplace@comcast.net Our online application is not working properly at this time.A Caring Place - All Breed Dog Rescue adopts throughout the Greater Chicagoland Area. All dogs and puppies live in foster homes, providing you as the adopter, with information on the animal's behaviors, needs, and requirements. We are always in search of fosters care providers. If you are one of those special people willing to open your heart and home to an animal in need and would like to receive information on how you can foster an animal, please contact us.

animal.description:
Ben is an adorable, fast-growing puppy with a silky white coat with brindle patches. We believe he’s a herding breed mix, possibly Aussie.  Ben is already exhibiting herding breed traits, nipping at heels and noise sensitivity, so we want to place him with adopters who have experience with herding breeds. He is a pup who will quickly become a dog who needs training, daily exercise and “a job.” Full-grown, he could weigh at least 50lbs or possibly 60+ pounds. He was born around October 6 and by late January, Ben already weighed 20 lbs.  

Ben is all puppy but learns quickly. He knows "sit" and is learning "come" and "leave it." Ben sleeps through the night and is crate trained. He’s doing well with house training but needs a home with someone who is vigilant and will continue his routine.

He likes meeting new people, playing with his toys, other dogs and being outside. He is still a puppy, so he is teething and must be monitored closely and instructed on what is ok to chew and redirected when it’s not. He enjoys playing with his foster Mom but needs to be instructed not to nip when he gets too excited.

Puppies need a home where people have the time and patience to train them properly. Young dogs need to go out regularly to establish proper housebreaking habits, so please consider this as you think about adopting this puppy.

If you are interested in adopting Ben, you MUST meet ALL criteria below (NO EXCEPTIONS):

1) You live in the Greensboro area. Ben needs the rest of his puppy vaccines and is too young to neuter, so we will do that at our vet once he is old enough.
2) Willing to housetrain and obedience train a puppy and are spry enough to keep up with a mischievous puppy—this is at least a 15-year commitment.
3) Have a fenced yard at least 5 ft high, preferably 6ft
4) An adult only home (or children over the age of 10)
5) Ben needs a home where someone is home most of the time (post-COVID). 

The adoption range for this dog is limited to Greensboro, NC. If you are interested in adopting this dog, contact h2hadoptions@gmail.com. 

An all adult home with a fenced yard (fence must be attached to the home) is required to adopt from Hart-2-Heart Rescue. 

There is an application process and adoption fee. We are an all-volunteer organization, and in addition to saving dogs, we have other responsibilities, so we appreciate your patience and understanding during this process. Response time can take up to 5 business days. 

Veterinary Care: All Hart-2-Heart Rescue foster dogs are spayed/neutered, current on heartworm prevention, parvo/distemper, bordetella, and rabies vaccines and are professionally groomed. As needed, our foster dogs have teeth cleanings, extractions, bloodwork and other diagnostic testing.

animal.description:
If you have ANY QUESTIONS or are truly interested in adopting any animal from PAW Animal Shelter Please, fillout an adoption application FIRST! WE are a high intake No Kill Shelter ran by a staff of 4 and do not always have time to answer every question asked by so many. If you are a good fit for the animal you are interested in -we will call to speak with you, If we feel you are not a good fit , we will contact you about other pets that may be a good fit for your home. Many people are losing the opportunity to adopt the animal they want because they fail to put in an application and the pet was adopted before we could answer your email. .If you have applied for an animal in our facility and have not received a response within 7 days, PLEASE call or contact us again. Though we do our best in trying to answer all emails in a timely manner, sometimes things get away from us, get lost or misplaced. It is never our intention to ignore a request about an adoptable animal in our facility.

Sandy Brown, Director, PAW Animal Shelter

319-372-2274

animal.description: Sweet Bridget is just about as affectionate as they come. Her foster parents can attest that this lovable doggo will make a lucky family very happy one day. If they weren't going to be so busy after this COVID mess, then they'd definitely keep her for themselves! Two broken legs may stop most, but definitely not this pup. Bridget still manages to waddle after her favorite humans, play tug-of-war with her toys, and snuggle with anyone and everyone. What she's missing in mobility, she definitely makes up for in kisses. This oversized lap dog wants her big ol' head in someone's lap 24/7. She quickly became her foster mom's shadow and will sit at her feet when she's working and sprawl across her lap when relaxing. Before you see Bridget you can hear the THUMP THUMP THUMP of her excited tail. Her smile is contagious and her goofy personality is a day-maker. Bridget is loyal, companionable, and expressive with her body language. She is potty trained and will stand by the door to let you know she needs to go out. She minds her manners, doesn't beg for food, and listens to commands. She does great in the car and is really just happy to be included in whatever's going on. While she does love to snuggle in bed, she also feels comfortable in her crate (good thing, too, because she's a bit of a bed hog and wants to sleep underneath you for most of the night). Bridget is a great companion and will be the best, most comforting new addition to the right household. Come meet her and see if this snugglebug is a good fit for yours and follow her silly antics on Instagram @bridgetthepiglet!

animal.description: Johnny Carson lives up to his name, which means spark. He's also quite the entertainer! He's an extremely energetic and intelligent dog who needs daily exercise, both physically and mentally. He loves to play, and will catch a case of the zoomies running laps around the yard. He definitely likes a wide-open space. He absolutely loves going on walks and meeting new people, where he tends to be extremely excited. Johnny is very loving, and will greet you happily when you get home from work. He also enjoys cuddling with you when you have a blanket, so you can watch your favorite movies and shows. He'll lay down with you when you go to sleep, he curls up in a little ball (which is an optical illusion since he is not small). He also enjoys napping on his bed or wherever he can find a space to curl up! Johnny will sleep in his crate, his bed, or in your bed if you like. He needs patience, and would benefit from more training. He shows great capacity to learn, and knows some commands already. He is still working on controlling all that energy, but he also has so many good habits. He doesn't bark too much unless someone gets close to the house, and is not scared of much of anything except a silly oven mitt for some reason. He is also a house trained pup who has not had any accidents in the house. This pup has allergies and will need to avoid certain foods to keep his skin and ears cleared up. He's a hungry boy and will go after anything on the floor. Johnny has so much potential to be a great companion! Come meet this adorable boy and let him entertain you!

She prefers being an only dog and prefers the company of people to that of other dogs. She loves car rides and having adventures, stuffed toys, and chasing balls. she walks well on leash and knows her basic commands. She is well behaved and respectful, house trained. She's very smart and picks up quickly what her people want from her. She is eager to please and wants people to be happy with her.

If you are interested in meeting Coda please complete an adoption or foster application on our website at www.happyheartsgsr.org. Also please follow us and get the latest updates on our dogs on facebook at www.facebook.com/HappyHeartsGSDRescue.

animal.description:
Are you looking for a smart, high energy dog who would enjoy training and being your running companion? Well, let me introduce you to Troy, a 40 pound, Pit Bull Terrier/Belgian Malinois mix who is between 1 and 2 years of age. Troy is a very loving dog who wants to snuggle and be close to his family. He absolutely loves going on walks, which he currently gets twice a day. Troy walks nicely in general but does get animated when he sees another dog. In addition to his walks, Troy goes for runs/jogs with his foster dad 3-4 days a week. In his foster home, Troy really enjoys the fenced in yard where, every day, he plays frisbee, chase his tennis ball, or play pull with his rope toy. If you haven't already noticed, Troy is a VERY active dog who requires a lot of exercise each and every day. He is also a very smart dog who learns quickly; his foster family is working with Troy every day teaching commands including sit, shake, down, and stay. Troy is crated when his fosters leave the house.

For inside the home, Troy requires a calm, more quiet household; a lot of activity and noise overwhelms him. Troy needs a patient slow introduction with new people and new dogs because he can be protective of the family; however, once he get to know a person, he loves them unconditionally. Because of this behavior, we are requiring previous dog ownership. He is approved for households with adults only or adults with older teens. Despite liking other dogs and wanting to play with them, he becomes over stimulated and doesn't know what to do with the added energy. Because of this, Troy should probably be the only dog in the home where he can receive undivided attention.

This dog has been examined by a licensed veterinarian, provided inoculations against diseases, been tested for heartworm disease, neutered, and microchipped. ADOPTION APPLICATIONS are available by request from acaringplace@comcast.net. A Caring Place - All Breed Dog Rescue adopts throughout the Greater Chicagoland Area. All dogs and puppies live in foster homes, providing you as the adopter, with information on the animal's behaviors, needs, and requirements. We are always in search of fosters care providers. If you are one of those special people willing to open your heart and home to an animal in need and would like to receive information on how you can foster an animal, please contact us.

I am house trained.  I would do best in a home as the only pet. I live with other dogs in my foster home, but it takes me awhile to warm up to new dogs. I'm too curious about cats so a home without cats is best for me. I make a great human companion. I love to cuddle and spend time with my human.

Do Not call to let us know you are interested. Follow the step stated below.

Adopter for Kissy must be at least 25 years old. Adoption fee is $550.00. She is completely vetted. Kissy is up to date on vaccinations, and spayed.

Kissy is currently in Texas but will travel to the PNW once an adopter has been found.

animal.description:
Meet the good, the playful, the silly, the affectionate, the highly intelligent, Lamb!! 

We also like to call him Lambo. 

This sweet boy is looking for a very special home. 
Lamb loves routine and expects you to stick to it! 
He is dog friendly, knows his commands and is looking for his special human to love and understand him. He needs an experienced owner who can advocate for him. 

Lamb would do best in a home with active adults and same size dogs and room to run and play. 

Lamb loves to play catch and tug and also loves to chill with his human and pup friends on the couch. He loves the outdoors, hiking and swimming. He would make someone a very great companion. 

Lamb isn’t a huge fan of thunderstorms or fireworks. 

Lamb comes with a behaviorist and trainer that will ensure he integrates well into the home and guide you with what he needs as far as structure so Lamb will flourish and succeed. 

Lamb is available for adoption through Forgotten Coast Animal Rescue, Houston. If you are interested in meeting or adopting Lamb, please first fill out our application 
https://forgottencoastanimalrescue.org/adoption-application

animal.description:
Snow is a sweet girl that has been dealt a crummy hand in life initially before she arrived at HONAR. She was bounced around to supposedly 5 different homes before she was 6 months old. The last individual that surrendered her was not able to care for her properly and address her simple allergy issues that left her with chronic ear infections and is said to have some scar tissue on her ear drums making her a little hard of hearing. Previous owners were physically abusive to her, thinking she was stubborn and not listening, when she just could hear everything. Snow has shown progress with a Salmon grain free diet and has stopped chewing feet and her ears are clearing up. She does hear and does well up close but if she was away from you a bit of distance, she may not hear clearly. Snow has learning "sit", "shake", "down" (with a treat), and "off". She is learning proper walking on a leash and we are working on not jumping on counters, people and/or jumping fences/gates. Snow is getting use to routine, crate training, and with routine/schedule seems to be housebroken. We were told that she would get into fights with the dogs she lived with prior to coming to rescue but HONAR has not seen any issues with the dogs in her foster home and she does well with the cats in the home, she can play a little rough with kittens but does not appear to want to harm them. She doesn't seem to be a dominant dog, usually happy-go-lucky, just wants to be with people. 
Snow is a very agile girl and would be an amazing dog for consideration of agility or anything requiring athleticism, she loves jumping and climbing. 
Snow is fully vetted, spayed, UTD on vaccines, HWT negative, and microchipped. Snow would love an active home and one that may have experience with Boxers and their active nature as well as someone patient with her learning new things and when teaching commands give her hand signals along with the word prompts.
***SNOW ABSOLUTELY HAS TO HAVE A PRIVACY FENCE for confinement, she WILL scale any height chain link.

Due to COVID-19 precautions, all animals for adoption through Homeward Trails can be met by appointment only. You can make an appointment to meet available dogs at our ADOPTION CENTER by going to https://www.signupgenius.com/go/20f084ea8ae2da5f49-meet and available cats at MEOW PALACE by going to https://www.signupgenius.com/go/20f084ea8ae2da5f49-meet1. 

For animals in FOSTER homes, please submit an online application and an adoption team will reply with next steps. We thank you for your patience as we work to keep saving lives during this difficult time.

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please fill out our dog adoption form on the website, or email messagemarybeth@gmail.com for any questions! 

PLEASE VISIT THIS WEBSITE TO FIND THE ADOPTION QUESTIONNAIRE:
http://www.homewardtrails.org/adopt-a-pet/adoption-forms/

Latte is a VERY shy girl, but has made AMAZING progress over the past few weeks! 

Hi! 
My name is Latte and I am looking for someone to love my quirkiness. I need someone who will be patient with me. I am finally coming out of my shell and seeking my foster brothers for playtime. I love toys and like to collect them all in one place. When foster Mom comes into her room, she will find a pile of toys and chew bones on her bed! Oh, I am also a hoarder of socks and slippers. If you are missing one you will probably find it in my crate! I like my crate and will go there for naps or if I get scared. Loud noises or quick movements make me run for safety. I really hope to have a dog brother or sister to play with and help me gain confidence. Cats are okay too even though they won't play with me. I am still working on house training. I use potty pads just fine but the big backyard is a little frightening to me. I need some help with leash training. I use to live in a very scary place but have now figured out not all people are bad and now like affection! I hope to meet my new forever Mom soon. I find men unnerving even though I now tolerate the 2 human boys that live here. (11 and 14), so maybe I can get use to one in time. Younger, noisy kids may be too much for me. I would be a great Covid work from home buddy. I am very quiet and happy to sleep behind your chair but don't be surprised to find a pile of my favorite toys behind you! 

Love, Latte

Latte needs a home with a good natured dog (or a couple) who will bond with her and show her that home life is safe. They must have a fenced yard for days Latte is not feeling the leash, as she is still improving in that department. 

She is not aggressive. Just getting used to living in a home! 

Please let me know if you would meet the above listed needs for Latte!!! 


Adoption Coordinator: Mary Beth Maggio
Location: Foster
The adoption fee for this dog is $475. This fee INCLUDES spay/neuter and microchip. 

We are proud to partner with the following veterinarians who offer a free first exam for your animal, exclusively for HT adopters: Caring Hands Animal Hospital, Palisades Veterinary Clinic, Sunshine Animal Hospital and Clarendon Animal Care and all VCA Animal Hospitals.

Additionally, any VCA hospital will cover illnesses up to $250 at no cost to any Homeward Trails adopter.

You can save animals like this one by becoming a foster! Fosters are like way stations between high kill shelters and forever homes. We need fosters so that we can save dogs before they are euthanized at the shelters. If you are interested in becoming a foster, please check out our information about fostering by visiting http://www.homewardtrails.org/foster-a-pet/dog-and-cat-foster-program

animal.description:
Ethan Onebrow was an owner surrender to animal control in southeast Missouri after the family decided he was too ill to care for any longer.

Ethan had several parasites in his body which caused him to be malnourished and bad body condition.  After a month in the shelter's care, he gained enough weight and underwent parasite treatment to gain weight to travel to us. 

Ethan weighed 38lbs when he arrived and is still underweight, but his foster's are fattening him up nicely.  

Ethan is a lover, he wants to be near his people.  He is highly intelligent and you have to be on your toes with him.  He thinks he can drive the vehicle despite being told he does not have a license to do so.  

He is crate and house trained, he will begin training classes for basic manners in the next week.  

He is undergoing heartworm treatment and is expected to have a full recovery. His adoptive family must bring him to our vet in Shorewood to complete his heartworm treatment.  

Ethan would prefer a home with a fenced yard to run and play in after he beats the heartworm disease.

Please apply do NOT send inquiries.
