animal.description:
Meet Morocco, or Mo for short. This gentle giant is a 1.5 year old pittie weighing in at about 68 pounds. He is fostered in a home with cats and is great with them. He spends lots of time with doggy cousins, small and large and also loves to play and spend time with some human cousins too. He’s extremely gentle and easy going and would thrive in a quiet home with a yard to run. He would do best in a home with at least one owner working from home because he suffers from separation anxiety. He needs a patient owner who is willing to work with him on it. 

Morocco is mostly potty trained and won’t have accidents in the house when regularly walked or let out in the yard. This big guys drinks tons of water and needs lots of potty breaks! He is also a master at learning boundaries and is a great listener. Mo is very food motivated and so far knows sit and is working very hard on paw and down! He is still used to being in the city, so he does need some encouragement when walking on busy streets. This guy is the perfect family dog and is waiting very patiently for his forever home! Adopt this sweet baby today!!

This pet's adoption fee is $425. He is being fostered in Brooklyn

animal.description:
Apply on our adoption application at leadrescue.org. We only adopt and foster in Illinois and only with 50 miles of downtown Chicago.

“You can have her. I want a Pomeranian instead.”

We in rescue all say the same thing: we could write a book. In fact there should be a recurring segment (like about those horrible dating stories) on late night tv about all the stuff we hear, see, wish we didn’t hear and see, and things we would like to forget. You will get a kick out of the things quite possibly excuses, even normal looking people, come up with to get rid of their pets.

Mishka was part of a very convoluted story. As part of the series of rescue books I could start, she would have her own chapter. The cliffnotes version is that Mishka had an owner who kept losing her. When returned, the owner seemed to think the way to discipline her was by using force. Obvs, that was and will never be okay. She got loose again and a caring woman found her. Through scanning for a chip, they were able to find the original owners. When called they said they don’t want her anymore and exclaimed, “I want a Pom anyways.” Although our blood boils over the lack of commitment to this dog, this was good news seeing how abuse and dog ownership shouldn’t go together. 

The chip company also made contact and eventually the chip was transferred to the caring person’s family. So if there happens to be a Pom on the street in Chicago at some point, well let’s just say I hope it’s not from the same owner. 

So the new family had every intention to keep this dog as their past Husky just passed away. But that’s the thing about a low key senior dog vs. a young, ready to run an Iditarod bolt of energy, you gotta be prepared to MUSH! Mishka was becoming destructive inside the home because she was just flat out bored. She even would throw her ball up in the air to try and entertain herself. But that only lasted so long. She instead realized 6 foot fence jumping looked like a better way to spend her days. 

Mishka is a 1.5 year old Siberian Husky, who every single person adores. She is extremely kid and dog friendly (bestie is a Doxie) and it was definitely tough to take her away from the grandchildren who fell madly in love with her. She does like to stare/chase birds and squirrels so cats are probably an iffy one. She is your supreme talky Husky but if you already love this breed, the talking isn’t annoying to you. Mishka really, really needs a family who wants her first, but secondly, who will be the person to throw the many toys for Mishka to catch, nonstop so she will never play catch by herself again. We believe she won’t chew your Timbs if exercised enough with another dog(s) or your wild n’ out children. Which leads me to tell you, she might have some separation anxiety and a crate will be your Godsend. Otherwise you will experience her opening a can of paint (her fosters were gone for 45 minutes), obvi getting it on her fur, and when they came home, in her excitement ran all over their bed with THE PAINT. Run, jump, squat, bike, she doesn’t care. Just take her with! Since she enjoys 6 foot fence jumping, she can live in an apartment with no yard and take her to the dog park or HAS TO BE on a tie out, supervised in a fenced yard. And lastly, poor girl throws up when she gets in the car, so always have paper towels on standby. You knew that CostCo membership was gonna work out for you.

One last thing to mention. It is very evident she got used to the abuse dealt in her short life. High hand gestures, putting her leash on too fast, or even just accidentally stepping on her paw or leash on a walk, her body language says it all. She cowers, ears go back, eyes squint, tail down. Therefore, she needs someone who isn’t going to even raise their voice in the home. Someone who can only show affection even if she runs around your home with wet paint. Someone who can rebuild her confidence and glue back together this dog.

If interested in not a Pom, not a Pomsky, and not a Shepsky, but a real purebred, amazing Husky, please apply for Mishka at leadrescue.org!

animal.description:
Hi, I'm Sheba! Also known as Miss Sheba or Queen Sheba. I'm a sweet and lovable 2 year old bull terrier mix whose favorite thing is to be close with humans and get all the pets and cuddles. I like to play too! Squeaky toys are my favorite, and I will play with them all day when I'm not napping at my Foster Mom's feet or following her around. Sometimes I'll even grab my Foster Mom's shoes or socks when she is not looking or paying attention to me, all so I can get more attention and love of course. I'm completely house trained, crate trained, and leash trained, and I love to go on walks. In fact I get so excited when it's time to go on walks that I just run around in circles! I do the same when it's time for food, too! I did have puppies in August (and I was a great Mom!), but they are weaned now and have moved on to their Furever homes. I'm also heartworm positive but I am currently undergoing treatment and the nice rescue that saved me will cover the cost of treatment until I test negative.

I would do good in a home that can give me lots of love and attention. I'm ok with some dogs, but it depends on their personality. I would probably not do well with cats because I tend to like to chase them. I like to be Queen of the house so any dominant dogs may make me nervous. I'm best buds with my foster mom's pup now but that's mostly because he lets me be Queen. I'm also good with kids. I'll even play with them a little! But I'd prefer to just sit and have them pet me. I'd do best in a home with older kids or kids that are gentle with me.

I'm ready to meet you and find my Furever home!

If you are interested in giving Sheba a forever home, please visit the link below to fill out an application! http://fureverafterrescue.org/adoption-application.html It is best to submit an application through a computer. We have experienced some problems when applications have been submitted using a mobile device. *When you submit the application, you are not obligated to adopt however it does reserve for you the opportunity to adopt that particular animal. We review them on a first come first served basis. If your application is approved, we will contact you and allow you the opportunity to adopt. If you choose not to adopt, we will contact the next approved applicant. If you have any questions or difficulties, please contact us and we will be glad to help!

animal.description:
Adoption fee on this dog is $100.

We are proud to announce the arrival of our super senior citizen, Sherlock.  At 13 years of age, this boy is humble yet loaded with colorful personality!  Because he was a stray, we know nothing about his former years except that he must have won Best in Show for Style & Stamina. One look at his face and you’ll agree that it radiates pure perfection. And despite being significantly underweight at 63 lbs, he is fueled with mental and physical eagerness to “GO”.  In fact, this boy can complete a 2-mile walk and at the pace of a dog half his age.  Shorter walks are highly recommended, however, to minimize his arthritic pain.
 
Sherlock shares his home with other female fosters, with whom he can display ‘pesty interest’. In fact, that seems to be his greeting style when he meets most other dogs.  Supervision will be necessary to redirect his intrusive curiosity.  After a couple days, this diminishes and he learns to ignore them.   When he is asked to engage in play, he will do his very best to reciprocate, but this only lasts a few minutes leaving his canine friends very disappointed.  In the home, Sherlock spends most of his time laying quietly on his dog bed near his human.  On occasion, he will chit-chat and tell you stories of his past. Nothing pleases him more than sharing his tales while getting a jolly belly and face rub.  You’ll be impressed with his baritone talent!  When left alone, Sherlock will express his displeasure by vocalizing with his deep howl.  This lasts a few minutes, then he settles down to rest patiently for your return. He is not destructive and finds little interest in chew toys or dog bones.  
 
Sherlock sleeps in a crate during the night and is housebroken using a dog door.  He receives human assistance using a cloth hip sling when climbing up a long flight of stairs, but he can descend on his own with cautious ease. He is friendly to all humans, however care should be taken with small active children because of his diminished eyesight.  He is outright eager to go on car rides, and requires gentle assistance getting in the vehicle. Because he is mentally and physically ready to move forward, attention must be given to estimate his lasting endurance so he can return safely and comfortably. 
 
As expected with many dogs his age, Sherlock has moderate kidney disease and arthritis.  This is managed with dietary modification and one daily pain medication.  He can be a picky eater, so his favorite tasty morsels are always included to enhance his pleasure in life.  
 
Let us know if you would like to meet this special boy. Few dogs offer us the opportunity to share in their last years with safety, dignity and joy.  He will repay you with his charming songs of gratitude. 
 
Small dogs, critters and cats unknown.

This dog is a Level 2. Please be sure you understand what a dog of this Level requires. Go to our GCGSR Dogs page for an explanation of the Dog Rating Levels.

For more information and to see when this dog will be attending an Adoption Day, please see our Dogs page on our main website at www.gcgsr.org. 

We operate within a reasonable driving distance from the Greater Sacramento area, the 	Central Valley down to Merced, and Lake Tahoe. A reasonable driving distance is determined by where one of our volunteers is willing to drive within our areas of service. That means we don't adopt out of our area, to Southern California, or Out of State. 

Thank you for visiting!

animal.description:
Amazing adopter needed for an amazing dog! Penny’s foster parents can’t say enough good things about our sweet, sweet, sweet Penny. Penny is a special girl who needs an adopter who will be patient and understanding of her fear of new people. Penny is not the type of dog who enjoys “socializing” and meeting new people, however when it comes to her people at home, she is such a LOVE. It didn’t take Penny long to warm up in her foster home and once she did, her silly, playful, goofy, truly amazing personality began to shine. And did we mention snuggly? Penny is such a loving, sweet, affectionate dog, making her the all-time favorite of her foster parents.

Penny, nervous at first, may appear to be a low energy dog, but she is actually a very typical playful, fun, athletic young dog. She loves to run and play and enjoys her walks. Check out her video to see how well she is doing with leash walking. Penny is very food motivated and has proven to enjoy her training sessions very much. She is so super smart and would love a home who will continue with her training, as she absolutely loves it! 

Penny walking on leash: https://youtu.be/VoxEN6BTG34

Penny also loves car rides, is housebroken and crate trained. Due to her general nervousness with new people, she will do best with a savvy adopter - and no kids. Also due to her intelligence and energy level, she will do best with someone who will continue to keep her mind and body engaged via both mental exercise (obedience and other activities) as well as regular physical exercise (hiking, jogging, etc.). 

She is approx. 1.5 years old, spayed, microchipped and vaccinated. Please note that the first step in our process is the adoption application found on our website www.midatlanticbullybuddies.org.

animal.description:
Atlas is a HW positive ~ 2 year old male retriever mix.  He has recently finished the fast kill HW treatment and is doing well.  He has gained weight and is now about 55-60 pounds.  He loves all people, but he is particularly fond of women. As his foster mom, he follows me everywhere and is my constant shadow.  He listens well and I can take him for walks without a leash in the yard.  He is crate trained and sleeps well in his crate all night.  He loves to go on rides and sits well in the car without moving around.  His favorite activity is to ride to the end of the driveway and wait for the bus with my two daughters.  He is not aggressive with my other two dogs or my cat (he doesn’t even notice the cat).  He should be ready for adoption in February after he has fully recovered from his fast kill treatment.  

All dogs come with a microchip, annual vaccinations including EBR rabies license and tag, dewormer, vet exam and spay/neuter. Adoption fee is $95-$175.

animal.description:
PLEASE READ BEFORE COMPLETING THE APPLICATION: 

Tilly is a special little girl that has a condition called cerebella hyperplasia. She is amazing and super sweet with the people she loves, but is defensive when meeting new people and will bite if people try to touch her without her knowing them well. Her condition makes it difficult to stand up and walk, but she does not let that stop her! When given access Tilly will get food and water as she needs it and is mostly potty trained if taken outside on a regular basis. She likes to do things on her own, she is Little Miss Independent, and can get upset if you try to do things for her. She would do well in a home that will give her the time to trust and provide lots of positive incentives (treats) as they get to know her. She would need to live with other dogs that are very predictable and safe since her condition makes her very vulnerable. She would also need a home where she is inside with short supervised play time outside in an area with no pools or other bodies of water that she could fall into. If you think she might be the right girl for you, please fill out the online application.

 What is Cerebellar Hypoplasia?
The symptoms of cerebellar hypoplasia are often not noticed at birth, and may not be noticed until the pet begins to be more active from around 6 weeks of age. Incoordination, jerky movements, and tremors may indicate the condition. 

Although there is no treatment for this disorder, often pets can go on to live quality lives. As this disorder can present similarly to other conditions it is important to discuss any concerns you may have that your pet is suffering from this disorder with your veterinarian.

The cerebellum is the part of the brain responsible for coordination, balance, and depth perception. Cerebellar hypoplasia is a congenital disorder in which the cerebellum is not completely matured at birth. This can be caused by a genetic disposition that affects some canine breeds or a number of conditions affecting the pregnant bitch, such as infection, poisoning, and malnutrition

animal.description:
Luey is a tiny guy at only 17 lbs, but he is ALL sweetness! Luey was found as a stray in North Carolina and recently made his way to BRSM. He is about 7 years old we think, and has been neutered. Luey is heartworm positive; this will be treated at the vet. As you can see from the pictures Luey is as cute as can be. He's still a little timid, but he happily joins his foster beagle brothers and sisters in playing, barking, and general beagle antics. He loves food, and loves being where he can keep an eye on his foster mom. He does bark a bit when she leaves, so care will need to be taken if he goes to an apartment or townhome. He is happy to go in a crate if needed and does not try to destroy anything in the home. Luey is just a doll who will make the right family or person very happy!

Luey's Webpage - http://beaglemaryland.org/brsm_ms/vIndividualCurrentDog.aspx?dogid=69872
Adoptable Dog Webpage - http://beaglemaryland.org/brsm_ms/vCurrentDogs.aspx

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
HAAYY! I'm Willa. I'm pretty cute, I know. I'm searching for the perfect last name. I know you think you NEED this puppy, but let me tell you what I need!

I have a condition called Megaesophagus. Simply put, my food doesn't make it to my stomach if I don't sit just right. I have to sit in a special chair when I eat, and the humans make me stay there for about 15 minutes. Sitting upright allows gravity to push my food to my belly.

As you can see.. I'm skinny. So I REALLY need that food to get to my belly so I can grow to be big and strong. I'm just about 5 months old. With proper care, nutrition, and a good doctor to help guide my new family, I can live a long and healthy life! I love to play with the other dogs in my foster home, and the kitties are so fun to chase. Foster mom tries to tell me not to chase them, but...Kitties! They run because they want me to chase, right?

Anywho, I gotta go play now. If you think you can give me the proper care, let the nice people here know. If you have questions, ASK! They will be VERY picky about what last name I get. I'm just THAT special!

Willa is current on vaccines, microchipped and heartworm negative

animal.description:
Hudson is an adorable 17 month old pointer mix who came to rescue after he previous owners were no longer able to care for him & surrendered him to a local animal control. He had lived a very sheltered life before coming into rescue, but he spent some time in foster based training & is really coming out of his shell! 

He loves to go walks & play with his squeaky toys! He is also knows sit, paw, & down! He has gained lots of confidence with meeting new people & other animals & he is willing to do just about anything for food! 

Hudson would do best with an active family that has shy dog experience. He would do best in a home with older children. Hudson has been working on meeting new dogs & has been doing well, but can be selective about the dogs he likes due to a past trauma in his life. He may be willing to share his home with another dog, but is also more than happy being your one & only! 

We want to set Hudson up for success, and therefore would like to place him in a foster-to-adopt home, to make certain that the placement is the right one for both Hudson and the family.

To apply to foster-to-adopt, please fill out the application at our website - https://www.furryfriendsct.org/foster-application

Axl was surrendered to the Palmdale shelter for alleged aggression shown towards neighbors cat. This very handsome boy is so loving, sweet and full of energy. Axl is well trained in basic commands and tricks, walks well on leash, house broken, crate trained, and an overall really good dog. I'm 13-years-old and I'd really love a good family. When you see me, you're going to notice that my front paws look a little weird. I'm kind of like Nemo with his "special fin." I was born with a birth defect but it doesn't stop me from cruising around town! I just want to be loved and snuggled, and have a special human to love on. 

I've got a bit of arthritis (I mean, who doesn't at this age?! Am I right?) and sometimes I need a little help to pee or poop. It's embarrassing for me because I don't like asking for help, but you do what you gotta do when you gotta doo doo. 

I'm on a med called Petandim which keeps my coat shiny, makes me more playful (as if I needed help in that department) and it makes my joints feel better. 

I would love to meet you and see if we are a good fit. You can stop by Oldies But Goodies any day. I've cleared my schedule this week so we can have some quality time. 1750 S. Rainbow Blvd # 10. Open 10-7 weekdays and 10-5 weekends.

animal.description:
This adorable guy is Luke! Luke had a rough start, coming to rescue from a hoarding situation, and is now looking for the good life in a furever home! He would love a family that will give him his space to roam in a securely fenced in yard (he will require a 6 ft fence). Luke can be nervous in new situations but is very sweet once he warms up and gets familiar. He has a mild temperament and is happiest relaxing in the yard, calmly keeping watch over his humans. Luke is looking for a family that has experience with the breed and understands how to give a sometimes anxious Pyr their space - he will be the Pyrfect companion for these type of humans. With a little patience and a lot of love, Luke will be a wonderful addition - apply for this adorable guy today!

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/adoptable-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed. 

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.

animal.description:
Age: 2 years
Gender: Male
Weight: 70lbs
Energy Level: Moderate
Overall Drive: Moderate
Location: Monroe, WA

Toddy is a lovable guy who longs for all the attention he can get from his handler, and as such is always within reach to receive scratches and belly rubs. If he were a human, he would be a professional athlete: he has endless amounts of energy and is extremely coordinated and agile. He loves to run and will play with anything that can be thrown or caught.

Toddy can be very eager but is easily distracted while out away from the house. He can be slightly reactive to both people and dogs when on leash and can struggle refocusing when there is lots of activity around him. He will need continued work with a skilled handler to ensure his focus stays on task. Toddy has played well with other dogs off leash and has also done well meeting new people when not on leash. Due to his high prey drive and high energy, he would likely do best in a home without cats, small animals, or children. Toddy rides well in the car, doesn’t react to loud noises aside from the occasional bark, and is fully crate trained though will sometimes protest being in his crate during the day. He is working on mastering basic obedience and ensuring he is chewing appropriately. Toddy will need an experienced handler who can provide him with structure and support while he continues to learn how to harness his energy and drive.

Toddy would do best in an active household where he could be included in all the hustle and bustle. He has lots of love and energy to give, and with the right handler he will continue to blossom into an amazing companion and partner. Looking for a goofy, athletic, and eager dog who is ready to give all of himself to you? Toddy is ready to meet you!

WEST COAST ADOPTIONS ONLY

Must have previous or current, purebred Malinois experience OR other high drive working breed experience

Our adoption process includes- completion of an application, followed by a telephone interview. If that goes well, we will arrange for a home visit.
Adoption Fee: $500.00. Transport along Interstate 5 (Bakersfield, CA to Bellingham, WA) is available but cost not included in adoption fee. 

Please visit www.woofproject.org and fill out an adoption application located here https://www.woofproject.org/application

animal.description: You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.~~Hi, my name is Echo and I'm a gorgeous two year old, 70 pound sable boy! I have lots of energy so if you like to run, I'm the doggie companion for you. I'm searching for my fur-ever family. I really enjoy walks outdoors, getting scratches, and playing with my foster brother. My ideal family would be me, my foster parent(s) and maybe a fur brother or sister to play with. I'm friends with all of the dog friends I meet. I recently learned that I do well with calm older children (over 12) but not so much with small children - I don't understand what to think of the loud noises they make and their energy is something else! I'm looking for a family who has time to train me, and give me lots of love. A fenced in yard for exercise is a plus, too! My favorite place to be is next to my human(s). I love them so much that when I'm in the car with them, I'll bark really loudly when someone walks up. I just want my family to know STRANGER DANGER!! At night, I sleep in their bedroom and alligator roll all over the bed until they send me to my bed, tuck me in and tell me goodnight. My foster parents say I'm doing well with leash manners but sometimes I'll try to go for a squirrel or a bunny if I see one. My prey drive is one reason why I should not live with cats. My foster family is working on basic manners with me. Right now, I can sit and shake for food. Why would I do it if there is no pepperoni involved?! Sometimes I get in trouble for counter surfing, but who wouldn't steal chicken from the counter when no one's watching? My people also don't love when I mouth them, but I can't help it when I want pets or get too excited. Sometimes their hands and arms just end up in my mouth! I'd never do anything to hurt them though. I am extremely protective of my people when visitors come to my house or approach my car. For this reason, I will need an experienced German Shepherd owner that is willing to help me become my best self. If you think you'd like to get a chance to know me better, please reach out to your adoption coordinator. If you do not have an adoption coordinator, please fill out an adoption application at https://freedomgermanshepherdrescue.org. I am being fostered near Fayetteville. Love, Echo

animal.description:
Boo was adopted out as a puppy almost 10 years ago and he thought he was home for good. But he was recently returned to us because the stress of a new baby in the house made him very anxious and protective. We feel that Boo really needs a quiet, adult-only home with someone who can give him the time and attention he craves and has been missing. Boo will follow his people from room to room, just wanting to be near them. He does still have high energy, even as a senior dog. He can be very strong on a leash and is a little stubborn when he wants to be. Boo also prefers females over males but is capable of loving both! The best home for him would be one who has few visitors as he bonds strongly with his owners.

Boo has never lived with another dog, and can be selective with them when meeting on walks, etc., so we are not sure how he would do with another dog in the home. He does have a high prey drive, so cats would also be a definite "no".

If you are interested in Boo, please fill out an application today at www.ehrdogs.org. We would really love to see this poor boy back in a home after having had one for ten years.

animal.description:
Lola is a 1-2 year old Shar Pei mix. Lola, along with her human owner, her 6 four-day-old puppies, 3 furry sisters, and 2 furry brothers were evicted from their home last October. Luckily, when asked to help, we had room for all the dogs in the family. Lolas puppies have now all found their forever homes and she is looking for hers. She is very bright. You must gain her trust before being accepted. Fortunately, she is easily persuaded with patience and treats. When she allows you to join Team Lola, it is fast friendship. She is quick as lightening and is expert at the worlds fastest zoomies. She is a medium sized dog and is fully house trained. She played well with the other dogs she lived with in her previous home, but a meet and greet with any other resident dogs would be a must. A physical fence is required. 

AHeinz57 Pet Rescue and Transport is a 501c3 no-kill animal rescue located in De Soto, Iowa. Our pets are located at our facility and in foster homes around Central Iowa. We do adopt to out of town applicants, however we do require new family members be picked up in person. 

If you are interested in meeting one of our adorable adoptables, the first step in our process is to complete an adoption application. To complete an application or read more about our adoption process, please visit our website:

https://www.aheinz57.com/adopt-a-pet/adoption-process/
Our adoption fees are:

$300 - Puppies (up to 6 months)

$195 - Dogs age 6 months - 7 years

$100 - Senior Dogs (age 8 and up)

$200 - Bonded Buddies

$100 - Kittens (up to age 6 months)

$150 - 2 Kittens

$60 - Cats age 6 months and up

$90 - 2 Cats

For the most up-to-date listing of adoptable animals, please visit our website: https://www.aheinz57.com/adopt-a-pet/

Thank you for considering adopting a rescue animal!

animal.description: Drake is an approximately 5 year old black male who came from a shelter in upstate New York. Sadly Drake has tested positive for Heartworm and will need Heartworm treatment. He was recently neutered and will be starting his Heartworm treatment in October once recovered from his neuter. On top of all of that, Drake has a serious happy tail. His foster mom is working hard to heal it and we are hopeful it will not need to be amputated. It will take a good two months of careful wrapping and protection to do that. Drake had a double ear infection and needed antibiotics to treat that. The antibiotics then caused quite the tummy upset. Since then, Drake has had a hard time adjusting to several diets that his foster mom has tried and is suffering with colitis. His foster mom is working on finding the right combination of foods, probiotics and supplements to get that under control. Despite all these issues, Drake is so sweet! He loves everyone and gets along with all the dogs in his foster home. He is constantly wagging that long strong tail and hence the challenge of keeping it bandaged. The current methods seem to be working. Once Drake starts his Heartworm treatment he will need to be on crate rest and limited activity for at least two months. Drake certainly has been a challenge to care for but is worth all the efforts on his behalf, he is an absolute love and whoever is lucky enough to take him home will have a wonderful Dane companion. Drake came to MAGDRL in September of 2020 (3). For more info on this dog and our adoption policies, visit NJ MAGDRL at http://www.magdrl-nj.com/our-dogs/ .  MAGDRL adopts Great Danes in NY, NJ, PA, MD, DE, DC, VA & WV.

animal.description:
Hayla is a six month-old shar-pei mix. She is about 25 pounds now, and she will likely end up around 30-35 pounds full-grown. She is playful, high-energy, and very well-behaved. We are working on basic commands and she is good walking on a leash. Hayla is crate-trained and quiet in her crate. She is also quiet around the house, and she gets along incredibly well with my two older dogs. She would likely appreciate having a young, high-energy sibling for playtime! Hayla does have some issues with mobility and with pottying. She has seen a neuro-specialist, and the specialist said she does show signs of a spinal cord issue and/or issues commonly seen in "cork-screw tail" breeds. Hayla is incontinent, and she does not seem to feel when she goes to the bathroom at all. The specialist gave a poor prognosis for correcting this, and she will likely be incontinent her entire life. Hayla does very well wearing a diaper around the house! We are working on a pottying routine helping her express outside.

Hayla's back feet are also a little uncertain. She has a very unique gait, but this does not stop her from running and jumping with her buddies! She does not show any signs of pain... It seems like she can't feel very much and doesn't exactly know where her feet land. Hayla does show a surprising amount of coordination despite this, though!

Hayla LOVES to play with other dogs, and she does well meeting new people and animals. She can get overwhelmed in new places, but with a treat and some kind words, she is quickly won over! She also finds a lot of confidence from being around her doggie siblings.

Hayla is a wonderful dog! Her personality is unique and adorable.

animal.description:
MEET KELSOS RIVER
 
Tiny Kelsos River already struck out as a racing dog, never having made it out of training school. We're convinced that's because her true destiny is as someone's companion.
She's a delicate, tentative soul who is seeking a special home where she can forget her worries and find peace and security.
At the top of young River's list of requirements is a quiet environment with people who are home a lot, and who are familiar with the Greyhound breed. She is not a hound for first-time adopters.
For a dog who never raced, River is quite athletic. Since we have been told she can easily clear a 4' fence, we'd feel better if she had a sturdy 6' fence.
She is startled by loud noises and sudden movements, so leash walking in the neighborhood is something that should be delayed until she becomes more confident. A two-leash system, one attached to a collar and one to a harness, is perfect for her at this stage in her transition.
Next up on her must-have list: another Greyhound or two who can show her the ropes. There's an unspoken language among Greyhounds that they all understand, whether or not they raced. River needs guidance and reassurance from her own kind as it will show her how to act, and react, to life on the outside. 
In the two weeks that we've had her, River has already made great strides. She sailed through her spay surgery, and even made friends with the veterinary nurses taking care of her. She has also been helped by her well-experienced foster parents, by the other Greyhounds in her foster home, and by the pheromone-based calming collar that she has been wearing for the past week.
One way in which River is not shy is when it comes to eating. If eating and counter-surfing was an Olympic sport, River would go for the gold. She is very enthusiastic and happy to munch away, seemingly without a care in the world. This means, of course, that training her should come easily since she is food motivated. Using a treat as a reward/incentive goes a long way.
Since River is only 14 months old, she is still very much a puppy. She is affectionate, and would be glad to have you pet her as long as you are will to keep going. She knows the phrase used in racing circles, "kennel up," and immediately goes into her crate for meals, and overnight. 
Right now, young River weighs just 50 pounds, but she is still growing. Still, she'll never be a very big girl, maybe 7-10 pounds heavier and a few inches taller.
We tried cat testing River when she arrived, but she was so overwhelmed by the new sights and sounds that she could not focus on the cat or anything else. Now that she's a bit more settled, we'll test her again.
River is a fast-learner who will soon gain even more confidence and be someone's best friend for many years to come.

Scooby loves everyone he meets, and he enjoys other dogs. He's about a year and a half, and he's a Bassador (Basset Hound - Labrador Retriever mix). He has a big ol' chocolate lab head and a basset body. He is a really sweet boy and wonderful companion. He enjoys toys, treats, and big soft beds. 
Scooby is excited to find his new family, and he has a few requests:
? Scooby really loves to be with his people, so he would like to find a home where someone will be with him most of the time.
? He gets a little nervous around unfamiliar doorways and will need someone to help him learn that it's safe (a few times in and out on the leash does wonders for him).
? Scooby is a laid-back guy, but he does love to play and gets the zoomies (for about 10 minutes before he crashes ? ). It's not a requirement, but he'd love to have a playmate.
? He loves going on walkies and it's important for his health to stay active. He'd like to find a family who will take him on walks.
? Scooby doesn't realize his size, so he would do best in a home with children over the age of 5.
He is a goofy, sweet, fun, happy, loving, well-behaved boy who needs a family to give him a little time to get to know them and to help him get settled in to their routine. In return, he will be your best friend and the best dog ever.

ADOPTION APPLICATION: www.tinyurl.com/IADRAdoptionApp

If you'd like to help Scooby while he searches for his very own family, you can sponsor him for only $19/month here: https://petbucks.org/pet/6208/sponsor/create

animal.description:
Hi! My name is Maple. I love going on walks and being with my people. Playing in the leaves is super fun too! I enjoy chewing on antlers and having my ears rubbed. I tend to get super excited at meal times or when being let out of my kennel so I might jump up or clip your fingers with my mouth. Don’t worry – I’m just happy and want to share my excitement!

I am a 2yo female pit bull mix from Tuba City. I love other dogs and all sorts of people. There are two things that I love more than anything though…and that’s food and giving kisses. Here’s why…

When I was rescued, I was very skinny and had been hit by a car, too. That car really did a number on my insides and even fractured my back-right leg. However, after a pretty intense surgery and weeks of bed rest, I am all better and raring to go! Sometimes you’ll notice a hitch in my gait, especially when I’m running. But this does not slow me down at all.  I even love going to Doggie Day Camp.  So many fun friends and hooman hugs! 

I would love to have a home to call my own and I really want another confident, playful dog in the house. I really don't like getting in trouble, so I need a hooman who will be patient with me.  A simple correction works for me.  Do you work from home? Maybe you don't go to work anymore and want a compact girl like me to add to your family? 

Maple kennels up easily and knows to go lay down (in a certain spot) and sit, and she rides well in the car. She is also a very fast learner.

Everyone at TCHS calls me their miracle dog – could you be my miracle?

Maple is up to date on her vaccinations, neutered and is currently being fostered in Flagstaff. Her adoption fee is $150

We are a small rescue/foster group without an animal shelter. If you are interested in meeting Maple, please fill out an online adoption application, located here: http://tubacityhumanesociety.org/tuba-city-humane-society-dogcat-online-adoption-application/ with more information about our adoption process here:
http://tubacityhumanesociety.org/adoptions/

Once we receive your application, which answers basic questions for us, we will have a conversation with you, before setting up a meeting. For more information, please contact Deb at dfranklin@tubacityhumanesociety.org or by phone at (928) 853-1046 (No calls after 7 p.m. please.)

Need a running buddy? I'm your pup!
I'm a gentle, sweet, social boy! I have lots of energy, so I'd love an active family. I am also very smart and love to stay busy. I'm learning my manners and I'm very treat motivated. I'm also known asa greatcuddler.I'd do best as an only dog and in a home with older children, 13 years old and up.

General Socialization Notes:

 I am very social and love every person I meet!I am high energy and I love to work and train and stay busy.I'd probably do best as an only dog. I can be a bit reactive on leash when I see other dogs, but I'm working on that. I have lots of puppy energy and am still learning my manners. I do like to chew things, so I need lots of project toys. I do well in my crate.

Does Jax like other pets?

I'd do best as an only dog and no cats, please.

Does Jax like children?

I have lots of energy and may be a bit too much for small children. I'd probably do best in a home with older children, 13 years old and up.

Favorite Toys:

I love my Kong, rope toys and bones filled with yummy treats.

Ideal Forever Home:

 I need an active family and one that is willing to work with me and keep me busy. I love attention and I really enjoy being with myhumans. I'd love a yard to run and play in. I'd also do best as an only dog and in a home with children, 13 years and older.

animal.description:
Benny is a 9 month old, 16lb chihuahua mix with beautiful eyes.
Benny craves attention and loves to be in or around your lap.
Benny has had some professional training in the past and is pretty obedient. He knows sit, lay down, and shake.
Benny loves people, and he loves children once he has gotten used to them but can nip at them for the first few days upon meeting them.  It only takes him a few days to warm up to children though, then he absolutely loves them!
Benny is very cuddly and loves sitting next to you on the couch and loves belly rubs.
Benny does well on a leashed harness when taken for walks.
He does well with other dogs.
He does well with free feeding and is non food aggressive and has no resource guarding issues.
Benny is a total love bug.  Adoption fee $400

All UnderDogs are spayed/neutered, heartworm checked, microchipped, up to date on vaccines and heartworm/flea/tick preventatives.  For consideration for one or more dogs, we require that an on-line application is filled out.  

TO ADOPT THIS DOG PLEASE FILL OUT AN APPLICATION AT https://underdogrescueofflorida.com/. 

Sorry, we do not adopt outside of Florida.  Applicants are subject to a home visit, and veterinary references will be checked. Please include a vet reference (including phone number) when applying online.

Our application process:
FIRST, an application must be approved for adoption from our rescue.
SECOND, we determine whether the dog that has been applied for is a "good match" for the household that wants to adopt him/her.  We take into consideration the dog's activity level, compatibility with other members of the household (human and other pets), etc.
If your application has been approved, but the dog you applied for is no longer available, please take the time and look over our adoptable dogs again.  We will make every effort to find the right dog for an approved applicant.

We hope you agree and understand that our goal to find the best forever home is our #1 priority! Please fill out an Adoption Application at https://underdogrescueofflorida.com/

animal.description:
Hera is not available for adoption.

She is battling a deadly fungal infection called Blastomycosis. Hera has been fighting the infection for 6 months now.

When we first rescued her, it took several doctors and a specialist to figure out what was wrong since the infection is so rare.

The fungus invaded Hera’s entire body. She was in an oxygen tank for 4 days, she couldn’t use her front leg, and the infection caused her to be blind. 

Now, after $16,000 in vet bills, Hera’s clinically doing well, but her Blasto levels are still high at 11.4.

We continuously monitor her blood and organ values as her antifungal meds can damage her liver and kidneys. She goes back for a recheck in January.

Being blind has not stopped Hera from being a normal pup. At only 1-year-old, she enjoys playing with other dogs more than anything. She has learned how to go up and down steps as well.

animal.description:
Beautiful Bella is ready to meet her new family.  This sweet beagle mix is about 9 years old but she has plenty of love to give.  We don’t know what this girl is mixed with - (maybe spaniel? Your guess is as good as ours) - however she weighs about 25 pounds.  She recently had surgery to remove a mammary mass and is getting back to being her playful self.  

Bella found herself in need of help after her owner passed away.  We were given the privilege to help her transition through her loss and find a new family to love.

Bella is dog and cat friendly.  She is good with older children who respect her boundries.  She is good on a leash, house broken, and crate trained. It took some time but she learned how to use the doggy door and now uses it like a pro.  This little lady likes to catch treats, will sit for you (sometimes) and respects furniture rules.  She is not a velcro dog but does like to be with her people.  She is pretty chill and loves belly rubs and a good nap.

As we know, no dog is perfect and so we share the faults.  Bella does guard her food and must be fed separately from other dogs to prevent issues.  She loves to dig and has a history of trying to dig under the fence.  It will come as no surprise that one of her favorite things to do is talk -  with her big beagle voice.

Bella’s foster mom tells us that while “no dog is perfect, Bella is pretty darn close to it”.  Could she be perfect for you?
_____________________________

The adoption donation for Bella is $200. All of our dogs are spayed/neutered, microchipped, current on vaccines, and on flea/tick/heartworm prevention. 

Our applications can be found at https://www.apaprescue.com

If you would like to meet this dog, you must have an approved application on file and be willing to travel to the Columbiana, Ohio area for a meet and greet.  All of our dogs reside in foster homes. We do not have a physical shelter.

Applications will be reviewed/approved, and each dog will be placed in the home that can best meet their individual needs.  Submitting an application does not guarantee adoption of any dog.

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Ruby was rescued from a high kill shelter in Texas. She is currently being treated for mange. She arrived to her Virginia foster on December 19th. Ruby is doing AMAZING since her move to Virginia. Most all of her beautiful coat is growing back, I hope her coat will be full and bushy by spring. She's eating and drinking very good, she gets a daily supplement which I'm sure is the reason her fur is growing so nice. We are introducing her slowly to our pack, 2 Shepherd s and 1 Lab. She is good friends with our Lab , she s very interested in our Shepherds but they are a lot bigger and stronger. This girl is getting her strength back, she's still a little wobbly in her hind legs. She has very little muscle so we're watching over her to make sure she's safe. She likes men and women, we have not met any children yet. She loves to play ball in the yard and sleep in her new bed, most likely her 1st one. Ruby I

s ok in the car no sickness , still a little unsure of where she's going so I'll work on making car rides a good thing. Her !st Vet. visit was good she loved everyone and they adored her, we will have her results soon so rescue can get her started on her heartworm treatments. We will be at events soon! check us out on the website and Facebook for her updates...If you are an approved adopter and are interested in this dog, please let your case worker know. If you are not yet an approved adopter but are interested, please complete an adoption application!

animal.description:
To be considered for adopting a dog from Canine Lifeline, you must have an approved application must be on file. Please visit http://www.caninelifeline.org/adoption-process/ for more information about our adoption process and to submit an online application.

Greeley is a handsome 1 year-old Beagle/Collie mix male who found himself homeless at an overcrowded rural county dog shelter and made the trip to Canine Lifeline so he could take his time finding the perfect new home. We don't have any history on his pre-shelter life but he's been a very friendly guy with all people he's met since coming to us. He's been particular about his dog friends though. Some dogs he meets and instantly starts wrestling and playing with them and others he doesn't like at all. He would not be a candidate for doggie daycare or the dog park and would need to be monitored closely on walks should he take a dislike to a dog he meets. We also want to place Greeley as the only dog in the home as he doesn't like to share his things with other dogs. Greeley has done very well with crate-training in his foster home so should be able to pick up the house rules quickly in his new home. Greeley needs a yard that has a secure aboveground fence to keep him safely at home. He would also benefit from attending an obedience class with his new family to work on his canine good manners. With some time and patience, this sweet dog is going to make a fabulous companion for his new one-dog family. Greeley weighs about 38 pounds and his adoption fee is $325. He's neutered, heartworm negative and on monthly preventative, up to date on vaccinations including bivalent canine influenza, wormed, on flea and tick preventative, and microchipped. As part of the adoption process, all adopters must commit to a two-week adjustment period to make sure it's a great match before the adoption is finalized. Please email info@caninelifeline.org if you're interested in Greeley. An approved application is required before we schedule meets with any of our dogs. Please note that we don't place our dogs in homes with children under 7 years of age. We correspond via email so please check your junkmail or spam folder to make sure our reply hasn't landed in there. Please visit our website at www.caninelifeline.org to see more photos of Greeley and to submit an online application if you live in Northeast OH.

animal.description:
Gumdrop- Female is the last of 6
This is how her foster describes her personality!

The positives: She’s super loving and cuddly (on her terms though)
She playful- loves toys- and likes to be outside running around our yard.  
She’s pretty smart: is food motivated and has sit, touch and down mostly learned - we have also worked on stay- off- walk- stop
We’ve been walking her on a leash in our yard a couple times a day and she’s doing pretty good on leash.  
Potty training is going okay- but only because we are on top of it.  She hasn’t had an accident in last two days inside- (but we are really on top of it and take her out every hour).

Here are the negatives: 
She’s bonding strongly with just me- (even though I’ve made it a point to make sure my kids and husband are fully engaged and part of the daily love and training and they’ve all been around her and home as much as I have since we got her) - she might be more of a one person type dog- 
She has a Chihuahua style tenacity about her that doesn’t listen and/or give up when focused/engaged on something she wants- but in a bad way.  
- she is possessive over me and reacts when my children approach 

She’s skittish and nervous at times- but the type that isn’t just puppy behavior- it’s more temperament 

We will be looking for an experienced adopter

These adorable babies were released to the rescue by their mommies owner she had several big dog mixes and was unsure of who their dad was. We stepped in had mommy spayed and got the puppies all their needed veterinary care, puppies are now de wormed, up to dat on vaccines and looking for their forever homes.
If you are interested in meeting them start by filling out an adoption application

animal.description:
Please complete an adoption application before inquiring about Remy.   If he is still listed then he is still available.   Please ready his entire description and if you feel you might be a decent fit, then we would love to see your application!   Be as thorough as possible with your answers...  Remy is a great boy, but needs a very particular home...    

Here is the link for our online adoption application:
https://www.emailmeform.com/builder/form/reDsnda01Xg1el09

Remy is a courtesy listing to help his owner find the right forever home for him.    He is a 4 yr old husky/shepherd mix, 75 lbs,  housetrained,  UTD on vaccines, microchipped and neutered.    Very playful and sweet boy!   However he is fairly leery of new people and can be dog selective, so is not a candidate for dog parks.   Knows several commands and has a good amount of energy.   Loves any outdoor activities, loves to swim and will need a physically active owner.   Experience required, he is not the dog for a first time dog owner or someone who is not a leader.    Remy will require daily structure, leadership and exercise.       A busy home with lots of people or kids in and out is not the right fit.    He bonds very strongly with his person and is off leash trained.    He would love a quiet home in the country with an active person who is home a lot.   Preferably who works from home or possibly retired.    (not required but preferred)   

Remy is currently being boarded at Liberty K9 Training in Barnum MN and potential adopters will be able to meet him there.   He has also gone through a Board and Train program there.   

References, home visit and completed application required.   

A note from the trainer!
Remy is a very high energy dog that will require a large fenced in yard, or a very active home that will take him for walks, hikes, swims, etc. Remy LOVES to run and swim. Remy has completed a very high level of off-leash obedience training. Remy comes back when he is called, waits at doorways, lays down and stays, sits and stays, knows how to "leave it", stay on place and walk nicely on a loose leash. Remy is very particular when it comes to other dogs. He enjoys being around other dogs, but only if they are appropriate and not too pushy. Remy also has some other behavior quirks. Sometimes when Remy is walked on leash, he gets very worked up when he sees other dogs - this is something that can continue to improve by utilizing his obedience. Remy will come with 2 free private lessons at Liberty K9 in Barnum, MN so that his new owner(s) can better understand his quirks and continue with his obedience. Remy is a lover and very social with people he trusts... but is very unsure of new people - especially men. This is also an area that can continue to be improved. Remy does not like small children as they often don't understand boundaries and are not very appropriate with him. Remy would make a great adventure buddy with someone who is active and willing to help him work through his issues.

animal.description:
Billy is a one year old pitty mix full of life and love! 
He had a rough start in life, but that hasn’t stopped him from wanting to show love! He’s overcome a lot!
Due to the abuse he received he lost use of his back legs and tail for a while, but he is using them now! He can play right along with the other dogs. The nerve damage from abuse also led to some incontinence but with the use of a belly band he does great and has made his condition very manageable and easy. 
He loves playing with his foster siblings and taking naps with his foster parents. He has not been cat tested, but he does loves kids or anyone else who wants to play. 
He sleeps through the night in his kennel but does fine out of it as well. He is up to date on all of his shots and heartworm negative. 
Despite what has happened to him, he continues to show unconditional love. Please consider opening your home to Billy!  

*Take Paws Rescue saves dogs from high-kill shelters in Southeast Louisiana, owner surrenders, and discarded dogs with uncertain futures. All of our puppies live in foster homes where they are socialized, and well cared for. An application will be required to make sure it’s the perfect match!

 If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting, the first step is to please visit our website to complete an application and read all of our FAQs: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/adopt 

**An inquiry/question on Petfinder is NOT an application. All known details about our animals are posted on their profile and updated daily. Other info would be discussed in detail with the foster during the application review process. Due to the number of inquires received (hundreds daily) we ask you submit an application on our website (a single application can be used for any dog with Take Paws Rescue).

The adoption fee for adult dogs covers age appropriate vaccinations, microchip, spay/neuter if not yet performed, heartworm test & appropriate heartworm treatment by the rescue's vet. All dogs in our care are also kept up-to-date on HW/Flea Prevention. Please see our website for more information. 

2020 Adoption Fee Scale for non-benefactor animals:
Puppies under 12 months - $300
Dogs over 12 months - $200

For additional information, including the adoption process and our adoption fee scale for all our adoptable pets, see our FAQs page: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/faq

animal.description:
This dynamic duo, Buffy & Rocket, have become best friends in foster & are looking for their forever family together.  Both dogs are wonderful, sweet, loving & fun young pups.  Buffy is very timid at first, she takes longer to warms up & want to snuggle by following Rockets lead.  Rocket is very curious, confident, outgoing & is a real attention hog. Both are still pups about 9mo and 1yr old and 10lbs. 

They are active little pups; up early to go potty (trained with a dog door), they enjoy the freedom to go out to run, play with toys, wrestle & sun bathe.  So an outdoor yard, a doggy door & secured fencing is required.  They bark when they play or at scary sounds & whine when left alone.  They still act like babies; chewing on blankets & stealing your shoes.  

As young pups they will need a family focused on their needs, with time to give them a ton of attention, be committed to training, give them positive encouragement, patience & understanding to help them to feel like loved family members.

Thank you for reading about our awesome dog. All dogs came to us from different situations and we often do not know much about their past, but they are rescue dogs who deserve a second chance and need patience on their journey. All of our dogs our are in foster homes all across the bay area. 

The first step of the process is you must submit an application in order to set up a meet and great or talk with the foster family. Once application is submitted the foster parents will contact you to chat more about the dog and make sure they're a good fit and can answer any further question. The application answers most of all of our questions and can best match you. If you do not get the dog you apply for we can use your same application for 90 days towards another dog in our care and simply forward your app to that foster parent. 
http://form.jotform.com/underdogca/dog-adoption-application

All dogs will be fully vetted (Spay/ Neutered, Micro chipped, DHPP and Rabies Vaccinated) and other possible vet care prior to adoption.

The adoption fee is $300, which is considered a non refundable donation

visit us at underdogca.com or follow us on FB and IG @underdogca
https://www.facebook.com/underdogCA

animal.description:
Ryker is looking for a foster-to-adopt - or forever! - home! He'd like to introduce himself to you :)

Hi, I’m Ryker! I’m an 18 month old staffy mix on a journey looking for my forever family! I’ve had less than an ideal start to my life, being passed from family to family until ultimately I was sold on Craigslist and ended up with a family who didn’t have the experience to have a larger, strong dog and luckily a group of dedicated people found a rescue for me!

I am a very strong and active boy! I’m looking for an active family with previous bully breed experience. I lived a very sheltered life before rescue, with lots of changes so my new family needs to be willing to initially allow me to acclimate to my new environment and be comfortable with new people, and be willing to utilize positive, reward based training with me! I have previous positive experience living with children, but I would likely be best suited in an adult home due to my energy level and size. I absolutely love to play ball, it’s one of my favorite activities, but I also very much love to hike and splash around in the rivers/streams on our adventures.

I am housebroken and crate trained! I know lots of commands like sit, down, paw, and stay! My leash walking skills could use a bit of work, but I’m very food motivated and a fast learner. I’m also dog friendly, but would do best with a dog similar to my size! I cannot share my home with cats or other small animals are just too excitable for me!

I am looking for an adopter or a foster-to-adopt family. If I sound like a match for you, please ask about me today, I promise, you won’t be disappointed!

To adopt or foster-to-adopt, please fill out the form at our website - https://www.furryfriendsct.org/adoption-application

PLEASE READ THE ENTIRE BIO ON THIS DOG BEFORE REQUESTING AN APPLICATION.  MANY OF OUR DOGS HAVE STRICT REQUIREMENTS FOR THEIR ADOPTION.

SPECIFIC REQUIREMENTS FOR BRAVA'S ADOPTION:

1.  6 FOOT FENCE.

2.  NO SMALL CHILDREN

3.  SHE CANNOT LIVE IN AN APARTMENT, TOWNHOME, OR ATTACHED LIVING.

6 month old female herding breed mix, about 15 pounds.
Brava is an active, bouncy herding dog type. She has a softer temperament and is not as drivey as her brother Custer, but just as active and athletic.
She tends to be the submissive one of the two to both humans and dogs. She would love to have another dog to play with but tends to bond to her human. She can also settle and snuggle at times.
She can easily go over baby gates and shorter fences. 6' fenced yard required.
NO small kids as she has shown some tendency to be quite afraid of small humans.
She is just a puppy so she needs all the things a puppy needs including manners, training, socialization and house training. 

Adoption contract and fee applies.  All adoptable dogs can be met at adoption events hosted every weekend. For a list of scheduled events go to: https://www.facebook.com/SmidgetRescue/events .  Smidget Rescue is not a shelter, and dogs cannot be seen at the Rescue location. All dogs are fostered throughout the Puget Sound area and are brought to the events where they can be met by prospective adopters. Additional pictures of adoptable dogs can be seen at: https://www.facebook.com/SmidgetRescue/photos_stream?tab=photos_albums.   All adoptable dogs are spayed or neutered at 6 months of age or older, and always before being placed in their new homes.  APPLICATIONS CAN BE OBTAINED BY EMAIL ONLY. Adoption process includes application, meet & greet, home visit and reference check. Email Jamie at smidgetrescue@hotmail.com or click on the CONTACT link on this page.  PLEASE DOUBLE CHECK YOUR EMAIL ADDRESS BEFORE SENDING.  We get a fair number of incorrect emails and Jamie is not able to contact potential adopters.  Notice:  We do not ship dogs out of state.  If you live within a five-hour radius of Seattle, WA, (such as Portland, Vancouver B.C., etc.), we can arrange for a home visit.  If your home seems like a great fit for the dog you would like to adopt, you must then drive to meet the dog at one of our weekend events or at the fosters home.

PLEASE READ THE ENTIRE BIO ON THIS DOG BEFORE REQUESTING AN APPLICATION.  MANY OF OUR DOGS HAVE STRICT REQUIREMENTS FOR THEIR ADOPTION.  

SPECIFICS FOR CUSTER'S ADOPTION:  

 1.   FOOT FENCE REQUIRED
 2.  NO SMALL CHILDREN
3.  HE CANNOT LIVE IN AN APARTMENT, TOWNHOME, OR ATTACHED LIVING.

6 month old male herding breed mix puppy, about 15 pounds. Custer is an active, bouncy, driven herding dog type that needs a savvy adopter to rein him in! This guy loves to run and play chase with other dogs but tends to be a bit dominant with other dogs. He is submissive to people, however, and will 'smile' at you in submission. This is not at all aggression. He would love to have another dog to play with. He loves to nip you from behind and bounce off your butt when you are walking. This is typical for the breed and needs consistent correction until he understands that there is a time and a place. He would love to do agility or go sheep herding to burn off some of his energy while you are building a solid relationship. He will guard his food from other dogs (not humans), so separate feeding is recommended. He can easily go over baby gates and shorter fences. 6' fenced yard required. NO small kids as his teeth are sharp and he doesn't understand that kiddos are not play toys. Once he has grown and matured with some training, he will be ok with 10 and up. He is just a puppy so he needs all the things a puppy needs including manners, training, socialization and house training.   

Adoption contract and fee applies.  All adoptable dogs can be met at adoption events hosted every weekend. For a list of scheduled events go to: https://www.facebook.com/SmidgetRescue/events .  Smidget Rescue is not a shelter, and dogs cannot be seen at the Rescue location. All dogs are fostered throughout the Puget Sound area and are brought to the events where they can be met by prospective adopters. Additional pictures of adoptable dogs can be seen at: https://www.facebook.com/SmidgetRescue/photos_stream?tab=photos_albums.   All adoptable dogs are spayed or neutered at 6 months of age or older, and always before being placed in their new homes.  APPLICATIONS CAN BE OBTAINED BY EMAIL ONLY. Adoption process includes application, meet & greet, home visit and reference check. Email Jamie at smidgetrescue@hotmail.com or click on the CONTACT link on this page.  PLEASE DOUBLE CHECK YOUR EMAIL ADDRESS BEFORE SENDING.  We get a fair number of incorrect emails and Jamie is not able to contact potential adopters.  Notice:  We do not ship dogs out of state.  If you live within a five-hour radius of Seattle, WA, (such as Portland, Vancouver B.C., etc.), we can arrange for a home visit.  If your home seems like a great fit for the dog you would like to adopt, you must then drive to meet the dog at one of our weekend events or at the fosters home.

animal.description:
Snooki is the cutest mama dog who was originally confiscated with a large group of dogs three years ago. She had puppies with her and once they were all with us, they were adopted out to separate families. Sadly, Snooki’s family fell on hard times and could no longer care for her so she went back to her original foster home and has been doing amazing. 

She loves all the dogs in her foster home and plays great with them. She would probably do best with dogs that are similar to her in size or larger with similar play styles. She is not a fan of cats though so will need a cat-free home. Her first home had kids, including a baby, and she loved them all and did great with them. 

She is truly the sweetest and once trust is established, she loves her people and just wants to be with them. She can be a little wary of men in the beginning, but patience and treats will change her mind. Her most lovable attribute is that one ear that always stays up and, of course, her infectious smile! 

She’s a great car companion and would love to go on an adventure with you! Interested in the world’s cutest co-pilot? Fill out a survey today at https://www.playersforpits.com/adoption-survey

animal.description:
Hello, my name is Margot! I am a 6 yr. old, 60lbs. Labrabull (Pit Bull x Lab Mix). 

- I count my lucky stars that the HIT Living Foundation brought me into their care. I was 21lbs overweight, walking was hard, nail polish painted all over my body. I had double ear infections and wounds covering my snoot. Now? I'm thriving and in love with my foster family.

- Love me and I'll love you 100x times more! I'm super affectionate towards women, men and even children 10+. I have never met younger kids, so I'm not sure how I will be. I am also great with other dogs and cats... so pretty much a great fit with everyone!!! :) 

- All the belly rubs please! I am quick to roll over and show my belly to anyone who I think will pet it!

- Even though I'm an adult I'm still like a puppy! I have tons of energy and LOVE playing.

- I love human connection and thrive in a structured environment that has set rules. 

- I have never really been in a home before my foster home, so I am still learning what it's like to live inside, and what the boundaries and rules are, like not jumping up on the table, etc. With structured play, rest, meals and cuddles I have become very responsive and actually THRIVE in this type of atmosphere.

- Even though I've never been in a home before, I am fully potty trained and have never had an accident in the home... I'm such a smart girl! 

My perfect home will be:
- With an active individual or family that doesn't have small/young children who is committed and willing to put in the time to maintain my training, and give me physical and mental stimulation daily.
- With a yard, where I will have enough space to run around and play
- With other dogs OK. I'm best with large dogs, and not small until I've been properly introduced. One of my foster brothers is 13lbs and he's pretty cool in my book!

If you see me online I am still available for adoption! If you are interested in adopting me please fill out an application here: www.hitlivingfoundation.org/adoption-application, and email a video walkthrough of your home and yard to BOTH Nicole@hitlivingfoundation.org AND Marta@hitlivingfoundation.org. Your application will not be counted as valid without your video. You will hear back from us within a few days.

animal.description: Do you love taking pictures? Perfect, because Johnny Rico is the cutest and most awesome camera ham youll ever meet! Johnny is truly one of a kind. You will never have another sad day because Johnny always knows how to make anyone smile with his quirky antics and his fun spirit. Johnny was born with 2 deformed front legs which causes him to walk on his elbows. It sounds like this would slow him down but, not a chance! He still does most things other dogs do but just in his own way. Hes such an active and happy dog! He gets around just fine but would probably be best doing shorter walks. Hes a major love bug! He wants what all dogs want; a family. A family that will embrace his differences and love him the way that he is. We think hes perfect, but we know he longs for a forever home. We do recommend that he be in a home with children over 14+ and he would be best as your one and only pet. Doesnt Johnny sound amazing? Thats because he is! Contact us today if you're interested in a once in a lifetime dog like Johnny Rico!

animal.description:
My name is Tyson. I was nothing more than to please my human, but I do need a family that is good at teaching/training, implementing boundaries and teaching me how to be a good boy. You know what things I've learned in just a week? Sit, down, look at me, and place. Commands, "come," and, "stay," are 2 things I'm still working hard at! I also have a lot of energy and like to be very active! Hiking, running, count me in! If I can't let my energy out, I tend to find myself in trouble, so a backyard and room to run plus other activities, are a MUST for me to be happy and not chew up your favorite slippers/shoes! I'm a loving boy though and my foster dad is pretty awesome and can fill you in about more!

If you are interested in adopting, please visit our website and complete an adoption application at www.elpasocountycanine.org/available-dogs

If you need more info please email. We only have volunteers and are unable to answer general adoption questions/questions about a dog over the phone.
Hi my name is Ellie Mae and I’m a 2 year old Decker Rat Terrier. I have been spayed, vaccinated, micro-chipped, and am now ready for my new home! I weigh around 16lbs.

Here’s the deal... I was surrendered by my owner. I was kept in a pen outside with two other Decker dogs and they kept beating me up. I got hurt pretty bad a couple of times. I do not want to be an outside dog. I am crate and potty trained! I have never had an accident in my foster moms home. I don’t tear things up so you wouldn’t have to crate me. I get along great with the other dogs and puppies at my foster home I do need a house with at least one other nice dog around my age. I do like to ride on a Gator, snuggle on the couch, and play with other dogs. You must have a fenced yard. If you would like to adopt me please complete the online adoption form. Adoption fee is $95.00.

To meet one of our animals and possible adopt, please fill out this pre-adoption form so it can be sent to the foster:
https://form.jotform.com/200005720739042
Some sites won't allow you to open the link--Copy and paste it into you URL or email us for a form. cimarronhumane@yahoo.com. We do adopt out of state but we do not ship animals, If you want to adopt one of our animals, you must come to pick them up in Oklahoma.

animal.description:
This litter of Valley pups don't talk funny, but they'll layer you with kisses.

With a guesstimated birthday of Oct. 5th, they were abandoned so it's uncertain what their mom and dad look like.

Each pup in this litter is sweet and loves people.  They enjoy playing with other dogs and snuggling. 

April 2020:  We are not holding public adoption events at this time.  Qualified families are being invited to appointments to meet specific dogs.  There are currently no opportunities to view multiple dogs and adoption events aren't being held at Tractor Supply in Lenoir.

Whether dogs / puppies come in as strays or owner surrenders, we usually have to make our best guess as to birthdate and breed.   

If adopted into a home with other animals, particularly cats, your new pet should be crated or secured when you're not available to supervise to insure a harmonious relationship.  

A vet reference is required to confirm responsible pet ownership.  We suggest first time pet owners look for an adult dog for companionship and to gain experience through another rescue or your local government-run animal control..

Adoption fee covers two vaccinations plus spay / neuter if using our local low-cost spay/neuter clinic (overnight stay required) and surgery occurs as agreed upon in the adoption contract.  Convenience fee equal to refundable spay/neuter deposit may be added if using our veterinarian.  Additional fees for 3rd puppy vaccination, refundable spay/neuter deposit, etc. may apply.  

We are an all-volunteer, foster-based rescue.  We receive no funding from agencies.  Available animals can be seen most Saturdays at Tractor Supply in Lenoir from 10:00 a.m. to 2:00 p.m.  We recommend interested parties contact us to pre-qualify for adoption so their new furry family can go home once paperwork is complete.  Fees are required in cash.  For more information on our organization, our website is www.petpartnersrescue.org.

animal.description: You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Grinch (TX) is a male Labrador Retriever mix rescued in Texas. Our veterinary partner estimates that Grinch is 5 years old at the time of intake in November 2020. Grinch is good with people of all ages and other dogs. Grinch was picked up by Animal Control and brought to a kill shelter. It's obvious that Grinch's life was one of neglect, abuse and cruelty. His skin was like concrete due to a severe skin infection, he was emaciated, weak and very depressed. And when perhaps he thought he was being saved, he was dumped on the dirty, cold floor of the shelter and he was still alone. But Grinch is no longer alone; he's now a Rescue Dogs Rock NYC dog and that means he will get a do over life and this time he will be kept safe, he will know what it's like to give and get love, to feel a kind touch and hear a soft, loving voice. Grinch is leashtrained, and he loves to play catch, cuddle on the couch and play with toys. And he makes an awesome office assistant! If you can give Grinch his do over life, please apply online to adopt Grinch (TX) at www.rescuedogsrocknyc.org.

animal.description:
When we brought in Lupa he had been abandoned. He was found laying in the street by a good samaritan and they contacted us. He was rumored to at one time belong to drug addicts that allowed another of their dogs to die on a chain, uncared for. He was very malnourished and he was very thin. Covered in fleas of course. We took him to the vet the very next day and ran a full blood panel on him and found he was also heartworm positive.  

When I met him he jumped right into my car and rubbed his head all over my chest and it placed it under my arm. Like he knew we would take care of him.  We did. He is now ready to find his forever home.  He has been treated for the heartworm disease and has gained over 20 lbs.  

Lupa is such a sweet boy!  He loves to be with people (kids included)  He is a big boy now at 80+ lbs.  He LOVES to eat!  He has been great with all the different dogs he has met here.  Untested with cats. 

Crate trained/House Broken
Gets along well with the other dogs
Current on vaccines
Spayed
Microchipped
Negative for tick borne diseases (Lyme, Anaplasmosis, and Ehrlichiosis)
Kept on heartworm, intestinal parasite, and flea prevention

If you are interested in any of our dogs, please go to www.howlatthemoonrescue.com and fill out the application.  Adoption fee is $300

animal.description:
Daisy is a nine-year-old Black Lab who has quite a story. This special girl lived in a car with her homeless owner for most of this year. Both Daisy and her owner had some significant health challenges and Daisy was diagnosed with diabetes this fall. When her owner became permanently incapacitated, Daisy was surrendered to the county shelter and we were able to rescue her.

Managing doggie-diabetes may seem scary, but it really isn’t. Daisy’s daily care is fairly straightforward and simple. She eats a set amount of regular dog food and then gets an injection of insulin immediately afterwards. She eats every 12 hours, currently at 7 AM and 7PM, but this can be tweaked a bit to suit your schedule. Her insulin and needles are purchased from the pharmacy at Wal-mart for $40 and neither requires a prescription. Daisy cooperates beautifully for her shots and she is a normal dog in every other way. 

Daisy is good with other dogs, both small and large, but she does need to be fed separately in her crate. She is great with children and she is very much a people-pleaser. For obvious reasons, Daisy absolutely loves riding in the car. She prefers to be your front seat passenger but will lay on the back seat if requested. Daisy is housebroken and crate-trained. She enjoys snuggling on your bed and sofa with you. Due to her past, Daisy has learned to be quite flexible. She really just goes with the flow. She’s a simple, happy girl and she wants to make you happy, too. 

Daisy is fully vetted -- spayed, microchipped, heartworm negative, and current on vaccinations and deworming.Adoption fee is $250. You can see more photos and apply to adopt her by submitting an application at www.sohfga.com.

animal.description:
Meet Rocky!

This handsome boy is just under one year old. He is a Chow Chow/Heeler mix. He came in to the shelter due to no fault of his own, his owner worked too much. He is a great boy who LOVES to play. He does have some training to do yet, but he is willing to learn! We are unsure of how he does with other dogs, but he does like to chase the cats. He does great with everyone, but he needs to learn that he trusts you first. Get your application in to meet this sweet boy!

Rocky is up to date on his vaccinations and is neutered. His adoption fee is $350. For any other questions or to request an adoption application please email Donna at djerickson1@hotmail.com.

animal.description: You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Rocket (TX) is a male mixed breed rescued in Texas. Our veterinary partner estimates that Rocket is 3 years old at the time of intake in November 2020. Rocket is good with people of all ages and other dogs. Rocket was attacked by a pack of dogs, and with no one there to protect him, he was ripped apart. His right ear was ripped off, one side of his face was ripped to the bone and we believe he has a broken elbow. Rocket was brought to a kill shelter and scheduled for euthanasia. But it wasn't Rocket's turn to die, as we heard about him and immediately grabbed him up out of the shelter and brought him to our veterinary partner for lifesaving treatment. We would like to have Rocket's forever home waiting for him when he is ready to take off, so if you have space in your heart to give Rocket the love he deserves and you can keep him safe forever, please apply online to adopt Rocket (TX) at www.rescuedogsrocknyc.org.

Ella is a bit timid when she meets new people or is introduced to new things but adjusts quickly.> Ella is house and crate trained> Cuddle on the couch with my human?-oooh yeah!> Ella loves to run in the yard and has lots of energy> Ella is super sweet and affectionate> Ella loves to play with toys> Ella rides very well in the car and does well on leashed walks> Ella loves to learn and her training sessions> Ella does well and is playful with other dogs> Ella does hover down when she hears loud noises or if she is being pushed into an unknown situation. She will need extra socialization to become a bit more confident.Ella is a very energetic young lady and we would love to see her in a home with a fenced in yard or an active family who can give her the exercise she needs on a daily basis (no dog parks).

animal.description: This really awesome girl is named Minerva! She came in with 9 puppies, all of whom have been adopted, and she is just waiting for her furever home! She is very dog social, and incredibly affectionate. She would do well in a home with children 13 and up (she is very bouncy and would knock a small child over) and would love another large male dog to play with...no cats for Minerva please. This dog is really one in a million, so if you would like to meet her please call 310-278-2935!

animal.description: Please contact Jamie (jamie@pawsandprayers.org) for more information about this pet. Meet Diamond! She is a 9 year old Pit bull that recently found her way back to Paws and Prayers due to no fault of her own, sadly her mom was going somewhere that Diamond could not tag along. Diamond prefers to be the only pet in the home, but they have said shes done well with some more submissive dogs. Diamond is a little shy when you first meet her but after a little bit of time she warms up. Diamond has some joint pain in her back legs which is normal with age and shes currently taking an OTC hip/joint supplement to help with this. Diamond is house broken, and does well in a crate. Diamonds adoption fee is $150 she is fixed, up to date on vaccines, microchipped and current on flea/tick and heartworm prevention.
